  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Normal TSH? Don't scan, just FNA!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with an asymptomatic thyroid nodule and normal thyroid function tests. The correct next step is Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) because it is the primary diagnostic tool to assess the risk of malignancy in such a scenario, especially when TSH is within normal limits.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNA is the gold standard for the initial evaluation of thyroid nodules when thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) levels are normal. It provides crucial cytological information, directly guiding subsequent management decisions regarding surgical intervention or surveillance. Unlike ultrasonography which characterizes the nodule, or a thyroid scan which assesses functional status, FNA offers a direct assessment of malignancy risk. A thyroid scan is typically reserved for cases with suppressed TSH or clinical hyperthyroidism to identify 'hot' (usually benign) nodules, which is not the case here.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Start antithyroid medication): Incorrect. Antithyroid medications are used to treat hyperthyroidism, which is characterized by suppressed TSH and elevated thyroid hormone levels. This patient has normal thyroid function, so antithyroid medication is inappropriate.\nOption C (thyroid scan): Incorrect. A thyroid scan is indicated when TSH is suppressed or the patient is thyrotoxic to determine if the nodule is 'hot' (functioning) or 'cold' (non-functioning). With normal TSH, a thyroid scan is not the initial diagnostic step; FNA is preferred to directly evaluate for malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Test | Indication (Normal TSH) | Utility | Limitations |\n| :---------------- | :---------------------- | :------ | :----------- |\n| FNA               | Primary diagnostic step for malignancy risk | Provides cytology, guides management | Non-diagnostic rate, operator dependent |\n| Thyroid Scan      | Not indicated as initial step (unless TSH suppressed) | Differentiates hot/cold nodules (functional status) | Radiation exposure, cannot diagnose malignancy directly |\n| Ultrasonography   | Initial characterization of nodule (size, features) | Guides FNA, monitors nodule | Cannot definitively diagnose malignancy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal TSH + thyroid nodule = FNA first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the nodule's characteristics (size, echogenicity, margins, presence of microcalcifications, vascularity) would be assessed. Ultrasound guidance is then used to precisely target the nodule for FNA, ensuring adequate sampling.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015 or latest). These guidelines recommend FNA for thyroid nodules meeting specific size and sonographic risk criteria in patients with normal or elevated TSH.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | FNA.(bcause thyroid function normal) | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Start antithyroid medication. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | thyroid scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) FNA is recommended for all palpable solitary or dominant nodules, independent of size. FNA is prefer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
