  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, poke it out (with a needle, for diagnosis!).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA). For a patient with a single solid thyroid mass and normal thyroid function, FNA is the best next management step to evaluate for malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNA is the gold standard for evaluating thyroid nodules, especially solid ones, to determine their malignant potential. It is a minimally invasive procedure that obtains cells for cytological examination, guiding subsequent management. The Bethesda System for Reporting Thyroid Cytopathology provides a standardized classification system for FNA results, ranging from benign to malignant, which dictates the need for surgery or continued surveillance. This approach avoids unnecessary surgeries for benign lesions while promptly identifying those requiring intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Thyroid scan) (Incorrect): A thyroid scan (scintigraphy) is primarily useful for evaluating thyroid nodules in the context of abnormal TSH or suspicion of hyperfunction. A 'hot' nodule (hyperfunctioning) is almost always benign, while a 'cold' nodule (non-functioning) has a higher risk of malignancy but still requires FNA for definitive diagnosis. Since the patient has normal thyroid function (euthyroid), a thyroid scan is not the most direct or definitive next step for a solid nodule; FNA provides direct cytological information.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) | Thyroid Scan (Scintigraphy) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Use** | Cytological diagnosis of thyroid nodules (malignancy risk) | Functional assessment of thyroid nodules (hot vs. cold) |\n| **Indication** | Solid/cystic nodules, suspicious ultrasound features, normal TSH | Abnormal TSH, suspicion of hyperthyroidism, 'hot' nodule evaluation |\n| **Diagnostic Yield** | High for malignancy risk stratification (Bethesda System) | Differentiates functional status, 'hot' nodules are usually benign |\n| **Next Step for Solid Nodule (Euthyroid)** | **Preferred** (direct malignancy assessment) | Less preferred; 'cold' nodules still require FNA |\n| **Invasiveness** | Minimally invasive | Non-invasive (radioactive tracer) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Solid thyroid nodule + normal TSH = FNA first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a single solid thyroid mass would be visualized. FNA is typically performed under ultrasound guidance to ensure accurate sampling of the nodule, especially for smaller or less palpable lesions. Ultrasound features such as microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller-than-wide shape, and marked hypoechogenicity increase suspicion for malignancy and would prompt FNA.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015 (updated 2023) recommend FNA for thyroid nodules meeting specific size and sonographic criteria, especially solid nodules with suspicious features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thyroid scan. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | FNA | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
