  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't poke a hot potato, scan it first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. A thyroid scan is the correct initial step for a patient presenting with hyperthyroidism and thyroid nodules. This diagnostic test is crucial to determine the functional status of the nodules and guide further management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA radioactive iodine uptake and scan (RAIU) assesses the metabolic activity of thyroid tissue. In hyperthyroidism with nodules, the scan differentiates between \"hot\" (functioning) nodules, which are almost always benign and cause the hyperthyroidism, and \"cold\" (non-functioning) nodules, which carry a higher risk of malignancy. This distinction is paramount as it dictates whether further evaluation like FNA is necessary for malignancy risk or if treatment for hyperthyroidism is the primary focus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): FNA from both nodules is premature. Performing FNA on hot nodules is generally not indicated as they are rarely malignant and are often the source of hyperthyroidism. A thyroid scan must precede FNA to identify which nodules, if any, warrant biopsy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hot Nodule (Toxic Adenoma/Toxic MNG) | Cold Nodule | Graves' Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| RAIU Scan | Increased uptake in nodule(s), suppressed uptake in rest of gland | Decreased or no uptake in nodule, normal/suppressed uptake in rest of gland | Diffuse, symmetrically increased uptake throughout gland |\n| Malignancy Risk | Very low (<1%) | Higher (5-15%) | Low, but can coexist with malignancy |\n| Initial Management | Treat hyperthyroidism (e.g., antithyroid drugs, RAI ablation, surgery); FNA usually not needed | Evaluate for malignancy (e.g., FNA if size criteria met); treat hyperthyroidism if present | Treat hyperthyroidism (e.g., antithyroid drugs, RAI ablation, surgery) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hyperthyroidism + nodule = thyroid scan first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a thyroid scan, a \"hot\" nodule will appear as an area of increased radiotracer uptake, often with suppressed uptake in the surrounding normal thyroid tissue. A \"cold\" nodule will appear as a defect or area of decreased uptake compared to the surrounding thyroid tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2017, 2023). These guidelines recommend a thyroid scan for patients with hyperthyroidism and thyroid nodules to assess nodule function before considering FNA.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thyroid scan. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | FNA from both nodule | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
