  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cough test negative? Hematoma's the narrative!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nRectus sheath hematoma is the correct diagnosis. The key differentiating factor is that the abdominal mass does not change with coughing, which is characteristic of a rectus sheath hematoma, unlike a hernia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRectus sheath hematomas result from rupture of the epigastric vessels or tearing of the rectus abdominis muscle, often following trauma or sudden strain like heavy lifting. The hematoma forms within the rectus sheath, a strong fascial envelope. This containment within the sheath prevents the mass from protruding or changing significantly with increased intra-abdominal pressure, such as during a cough or Valsalva maneuver, making it a crucial diagnostic sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (hernia) (Incorrect): Hernias are protrusions of intra-abdominal contents through a fascial defect. They typically become more prominent or change with increased intra-abdominal pressure, such as coughing, as the contents are pushed out through the defect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Rectus Sheath Hematoma | Hernia |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Valsalva/Cough Test** | Mass does NOT change/protrude | Mass typically protrudes/enlarges |\n| **Location** | Within rectus abdominis muscle/sheath | Through a fascial defect (e.g., inguinal, umbilical) |\n| **Pain** | Often acute, localized, can be severe | Can be acute or chronic, often associated with bulge |\n| **Etiology** | Trauma, anticoagulation, muscle strain | Increased intra-abdominal pressure, congenital defect, weakness |\n| **Fothergill's Sign** | Positive (mass becomes more palpable/firm with head lift) | Negative |\n| **Carnett's Sign** | Positive (pain increases with abdominal wall contraction) | Negative (pain decreases or unchanged) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mass not changing with cough? Think rectus sheath hematoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a rectus sheath hematoma appears as a well-defined, often crescent-shaped collection within the rectus abdominis muscle or between the muscle and its sheath. Ultrasound can show an anechoic or hypoechoic collection, while CT would show a hyperdense collection in the acute phase, confirming the diagnosis and ruling out other abdominal wall masses.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of rectus sheath hematoma (e.g., 2019) recommend conservative management for stable patients, with surgical intervention reserved for hemodynamic instability or expanding hematomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | rectus sheath hematoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) key word:\n not change with cough** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
