  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the urethra's broken, divert the flow, then let the healing grow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct initial management for a membranous urethra injury is a retropubic catheter (suprapubic cystostomy). This approach provides immediate urinary diversion, preventing further extravasation and potential infection, while allowing for stabilization of the patient and resolution of local inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuprapubic diversion is crucial as it avoids instrumentation of the injured urethra, which could exacerbate the tear, create false passages, or introduce infection. It allows the hematoma and inflammation to subside, creating a more favorable environment for a delayed, definitive repair. This staged approach significantly improves the success rates of subsequent urethroplasty by allowing for better tissue planes and reduced scar burden.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Foley Catheter) (Incorrect): Attempting to pass a Foley catheter through a transected or severely injured membranous urethra is contraindicated due to the high risk of worsening the injury, creating false passages, and increasing the likelihood of infection and stricture formation.\nOption C (Retropubic repair) (Incorrect): While retropubic repair (urethroplasty) is the definitive treatment, it is almost always delayed for 3-6 months after the initial injury. Immediate repair is associated with higher rates of failure, stricture recurrence, and complications due to tissue edema, hematoma, and patient instability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Strategy | Indication | Rationale |\n| :------------------ | :--------- | :-------- |\n| Suprapubic Catheter | Membranous Urethral Injury (initial) | Urine diversion, prevents further trauma, allows inflammation to subside |\n| Foley Catheter | Anterior Urethral Injury (partial) | Stenting, allows healing, less risk of worsening injury |\n| Delayed Urethroplasty | Membranous Urethral Injury (definitive) | Optimal conditions for repair, better success rates, reduced complications |\n| Immediate Urethroplasty | Rarely indicated, high failure rate | Avoided due to edema, hematoma, and patient instability |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For membranous urethral injury, divert urine suprapubically; never force a Foley.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA retrograde urethrogram (RUG) is essential for diagnosis, showing extravasation of contrast at the site of injury. Intraoperatively, one might see significant pelvic hematoma and a completely disrupted urethra, often associated with pelvic fractures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urethral Trauma (2017). Recommends suprapubic urinary diversion as initial management for posterior urethral injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Folly Catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Retropubic catheter | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Retropubic repair | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
