  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a thyroid nodule looks suspicious, just poke it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) is the correct next step. A hard thyroid nodule on ultrasound, even if asymptomatic, raises suspicion for malignancy and warrants immediate further diagnostic evaluation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNA is the gold standard initial diagnostic procedure for evaluating thyroid nodules. It is a minimally invasive, cost-effective, and highly accurate method to obtain cells for cytological examination, helping to differentiate between benign and malignant lesions. Ultrasound guidance significantly improves the accuracy of sampling, especially for non-palpable or complex nodules, thereby guiding subsequent management and minimizing unnecessary surgeries while ensuring timely diagnosis of cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Thyroid scan with iron) (Incorrect): A 'thyroid scan with iron' is not a recognized diagnostic procedure. Thyroid scans typically use radioactive iodine (I-123 or I-131) or technetium-99m to assess the functional status of a nodule (hot vs. cold). While cold nodules have a higher risk of malignancy, a thyroid scan is generally not the first diagnostic step for a suspicious nodule; FNA is preferred for morphological assessment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **FNA** | Cytological diagnosis of thyroid nodules | Minimally invasive, high accuracy, cost-effective | Non-diagnostic rate, operator dependent |\n| **Thyroid Scan (Radioactive Iodine)** | Assess functional status (hot/cold) | Differentiates hyperfunctioning from non-functioning nodules | Radiation exposure, not definitive for malignancy |\n| **Core Needle Biopsy** | Histological diagnosis, when FNA is non-diagnostic | Provides tissue architecture, higher diagnostic yield | More invasive, higher complication rate |\n| **Surgical Excision** | Definitive diagnosis and treatment | Therapeutic and diagnostic | Invasive, risks of surgery, permanent hypothyroidism |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hard thyroid nodule on US? FNA is your first move.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a 'hard' nodule often correlates with suspicious features such as microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller-than-wide shape, marked hypoechogenicity, or increased stiffness on elastography, all of which increase the likelihood of malignancy and warrant FNA.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015) recommends FNA for thyroid nodules meeting specific size and sonographic criteria, especially those with suspicious features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thyroid scan with iron | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | FNA | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Operative** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
