  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Leg pain + edema post-discharge? Think DVT!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT). The patient's presentation of severe right leg pain and edema, occurring shortly after hospital discharge, is highly suggestive of DVT due to the increased risk associated with recent hospitalization and potential immobility.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDVT arises from Virchow's triad: venous stasis, endothelial injury, and hypercoagulability. Recent hospitalization often contributes to venous stasis (due to immobility) and can involve endothelial injury (e.g., surgery, IV lines) or hypercoagulable states (e.g., malignancy, inflammation). The thrombus obstructs venous outflow, leading to increased hydrostatic pressure, fluid extravasation, and the classic symptoms of pain and edema in the affected limb.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute thrombotic disease) (Incorrect): While DVT is a type of acute thrombotic disease, this option is too broad and lacks the specificity of DVT, which directly describes the clinical picture.\nOption C (Acute embolic disease) (Incorrect): Acute embolic disease typically refers to arterial emboli causing acute limb ischemia (e.g., from the heart), which presents with the '6 Ps' (pain, pallor, pulselessness, paresthesia, paralysis, poikilothermia) and not primarily with edema. While DVT can lead to pulmonary embolism (a venous embolus), the leg symptoms described are not characteristic of an arterial embolic event.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Pathophysiology |\n|---|---|---|\n| Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) | Unilateral leg pain, edema, warmth, tenderness, often post-immobility | Venous stasis, endothelial injury, hypercoagulability leading to thrombus formation |\n| Acute Arterial Embolism | Sudden onset severe pain, pallor, pulselessness, paresthesia, paralysis, poikilothermia (6 Ps) | Arterial occlusion by an embolus (e.g., from heart, aortic plaque) |\n| Cellulitis | Erythema, warmth, tenderness, swelling, often with fever and skin break | Bacterial infection of the dermis and subcutaneous tissue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recent hospitalization + unilateral leg pain/edema = DVT until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing DVT, showing a non-compressible vein, intraluminal thrombus, and absent or altered venous flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease (2016) recommend risk stratification and appropriate diagnostic workup for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | DVT | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute thrombotic disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Acute embolic disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
