  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cushing's adrenalectomy? Give hydrocortisone, or they'll crash!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is preoperative hydrocortisone. Patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome, especially unilateral, will have suppression of the contralateral adrenal gland and require perioperative steroid coverage to prevent acute adrenal insufficiency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic excess cortisol production from the adrenal adenoma in non-ACTH dependent Cushing's syndrome suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, leading to atrophy and functional suppression of the contralateral adrenal gland. Upon removal of the hyperfunctioning adrenal gland, the patient is left with an insufficient contralateral gland, resulting in a temporary state of adrenal insufficiency. Preoperative administration of hydrocortisone ensures adequate glucocorticoid levels during the stress of surgery and the immediate postoperative period, preventing a potentially life-threatening adrenal crisis until the HPA axis and contralateral gland recover.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (postoperative fludrocortisone) (Incorrect): Fludrocortisone is a mineralocorticoid. While essential for bilateral adrenalectomy, it is not the primary steroid replacement needed for unilateral adrenalectomy in Cushing's, where glucocorticoid deficiency is the main concern. Mineralocorticoid deficiency is less common with unilateral disease.\nOption B (postoperative metatone) (Incorrect): 'Metatone' is not a recognized medical drug or term in this context.\nOption D (pre operative (drug for pheochromocytoma forget its name )) (Incorrect): This refers to alpha-blockade (e.g., phenoxybenzamine) which is crucial for preoperative management of pheochromocytoma to prevent hypertensive crisis, but it is entirely irrelevant for Cushing's syndrome.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Pre-op Steroid Management | Post-op Steroid Management | Key Physiological Basis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Unilateral Cushing's Adrenalectomy | Yes (Hydrocortisone) | Tapered Hydrocortisone (weeks-months) | Contralateral adrenal suppression |\n| Bilateral Adrenalectomy (any cause) | Yes (Hydrocortisone) | Lifelong Hydrocortisone + Fludrocortisone | Complete adrenal insufficiency |\n| Pheochromocytoma Adrenalectomy | No (Alpha-blockade instead) | No | Adrenal medulla removal, cortex intact |\n| Primary Aldosteronism Adrenalectomy | No | No | Aldosterone-producing adenoma, cortisol production intact |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always cover steroids for adrenalectomy in Cushing's to prevent crisis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT/MRI) would typically show a unilateral adrenal adenoma. Intraoperatively, the affected adrenal gland would be enlarged and potentially nodular, while the contralateral adrenal gland might appear visibly atrophic or normal in size but functionally suppressed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Cushing's Syndrome (2015) recommends perioperative glucocorticoid replacement for patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | postoperative fludrocortisone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | postoperative metatone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | preoperative hydrocortisone | ✅ Correct |\n| D | pre operative (drug for pheochromocytoma forget its name ) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
