  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt about an ulcer, feel the flow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nChecking pulses is the correct first step because it provides an immediate, non-invasive assessment of limb perfusion, which is crucial for differentiating potential etiologies of a lateral malleolus ulcer and ruling out critical limb ischemia. This initial bedside evaluation guides subsequent diagnostic and therapeutic interventions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn an elderly, hypertensive patient presenting with a lateral malleolus ulcer, peripheral arterial disease (PAD) is a significant concern. Palpating pedal pulses (dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial) is the most fundamental and immediate bedside assessment to evaluate arterial inflow. Absent or diminished pulses would strongly suggest arterial insufficiency, guiding further diagnostic workup like an ABI or arterial duplex, and potentially urgent intervention if critical limb ischemia is suspected. This initial step helps prioritize care and ensures limb viability before more complex diagnostics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (venous duplex) (Incorrect): While venous disease can cause ulcers, a venous duplex is a specific diagnostic test for venous insufficiency and not the initial, broad assessment for all ulcer types, especially when arterial disease is a strong possibility in an elderly, hypertensive patient.\nOption C (ABI) (Incorrect): An Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI) is an excellent diagnostic tool for PAD, but it requires equipment and takes more time than a simple pulse check. A bedside pulse check is the *first* and most immediate step to assess perfusion before proceeding to more formal diagnostic tests.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Arterial Ulcer | Venous Ulcer | Neuropathic Ulcer |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Distal (toes, malleoli, pressure points) | Medial malleolus, gaiter area | Plantar foot, metatarsal heads, toes |\n| **Pain** | Severe, worse with elevation, claudication | Mild to moderate, worse with standing, relieved by elevation | Painless (due to neuropathy) |\n| **Pulses** | Diminished or absent | Present | Present |\n| **Skin Appearance** | Pale, shiny, hairless, cool, dependent rubor | Edematous, hyperpigmented, lipodermatosclerosis | Calloused, dry, cracked |\n| **Wound Bed** | Punched out, pale, necrotic, minimal exudate | Irregular, shallow, granulating, heavy exudate | Deep, often infected, surrounded by callus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always check pulses first to assess limb perfusion in any lower extremity ulcer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, you would palpate for the dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses. Absent or weak pulses would indicate potential arterial insufficiency. A handheld Doppler can be used to augment pulse assessment if manual palpation is difficult, providing an audible signal of blood flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease. It recommends physical examination, including pulse palpation, as a primary step in the evaluation of PAD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | venous duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | check pulse | ✅ Correct |\n| C | ABI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
