  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the belly pulses, think aorta's woes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm (AAA). The classic presentation of a pulsatile abdominal mass, especially in an older patient with cardiovascular risk factors and pain radiating to the back, is highly suggestive of an AAA.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAAA is a localized dilation of the abdominal aorta, typically infrarenal, exceeding 1.5 times its normal diameter. Risk factors include age, smoking, hypertension, and diabetes, all present in this patient. The epigastric pain radiating to the back is a common symptom, often indicating expansion or impending rupture. The pulsatile supraumbilical mass is the hallmark physical exam finding, resulting from the enlarged, pulsating aorta.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Secondary liver metastasis would typically present with hepatomegaly, jaundice, weight loss, and possibly a non-pulsatile mass, but not a pulsatile supraumbilical mass.\nOption C (Incorrect): Renal cell carcinoma often presents with hematuria, flank pain, and a palpable flank mass, which is usually non-pulsatile and not supraumbilical.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intact AAA | Ruptured AAA |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- |\n| **Symptoms** | Often asymptomatic; vague abdominal/back pain | Sudden severe abdominal/back pain, hypotension, syncope |\n| **Physical Exam** | Pulsatile abdominal mass | Pulsatile abdominal mass, tenderness, shock |\n| **Imaging** | Ultrasound, CT angiography (elective) | CT angiography (emergent), bedside ultrasound |\n| **Management** | Surveillance, elective repair | Emergent surgical repair |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pulsatile abdominal mass + back pain + risk factors = AAA until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would see a dilated abdominal aorta with a diameter >3 cm. CT angiography would show the exact size, location, and extent of the aneurysm, often with mural thrombus. Intraoperatively, a dilated, often atherosclerotic, infrarenal aorta would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms (2018). Recommends screening for men aged 65-75 with a history of smoking.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal aortic aneurysm | ✅ Correct |\n| B | secondary liver metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | renal cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
