  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just treat the web, find the spider's source!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is US Doppler. While spider nevi are often benign cosmetic concerns, they can be a cutaneous manifestation of underlying systemic conditions or local venous insufficiency, necessitating investigation before treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSpider nevi are dilated arterioles radiating from a central arteriole, often associated with hyperestrogen states (e.g., pregnancy, liver cirrhosis) or localized venous hypertension. Before cosmetic treatment, it is crucial to rule out underlying venous insufficiency, especially if the nevi are numerous, new, or located on the lower extremities. An US Doppler allows for non-invasive assessment of the venous system, identifying reflux or obstruction that might be contributing to the nevi, thereby guiding appropriate management beyond simple cosmetic removal.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (No need for investigation) (Incorrect): This is incorrect because spider nevi, particularly if multiple, rapidly appearing, or in specific locations, can be a sign of significant underlying conditions such as liver disease (portal hypertension), hyperestrogen states, or local venous insufficiency. Failing to investigate could miss a critical diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Description | Common Associations | Recommended Investigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Spider Nevi** | Central arteriole with radiating capillaries, blanches with pressure. | Liver disease, pregnancy, hyperestrogen states, venous insufficiency. | US Doppler (for venous insufficiency), LFTs (if liver disease suspected). |\n| **Cherry Angioma** | Small, bright red papules, no central vessel. | Common with aging. | Usually none. |\n| **Venous Lake** | Soft, compressible, dark blue papule, common on lips/ears. | Sun exposure. | Usually none. |\n| **Telangiectasias (general)** | Dilated small blood vessels, linear or branching. | Rosacea, sun damage, systemic sclerosis, hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia. | Depends on suspected underlying cause. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always investigate spider nevi for underlying systemic or venous causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUS Doppler will reveal venous reflux or insufficiency, such as incompetent valves in superficial or deep veins, which would indicate a need for treating the underlying venous disease rather than just the spider nevi.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Phlebology (ACP) Guidelines (various years) for the management of venous disease recommend duplex ultrasound for evaluation of venous insufficiency.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | No need for investigation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US doppler | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
