  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, ultrasound the limb out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is duplex ultrasound. For a female presenting with bilateral non-pitting lower limb swelling, the initial diagnostic approach often involves ruling out common vascular causes, for which duplex ultrasound is a highly effective and non-invasive tool.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-pitting edema, while often associated with lymphedema, can also be a manifestation of chronic venous insufficiency or other systemic conditions. Duplex ultrasound allows for comprehensive evaluation of the deep and superficial venous systems, identifying venous reflux, obstruction, or deep vein thrombosis (DVT), which can contribute to or mimic lymphedema. Its ability to visualize blood flow and vessel structure makes it an excellent first-line investigation to differentiate vascular causes from primary lymphatic disorders, guiding further management. Early identification of venous pathology can prevent progression and direct appropriate treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT angio) (Incorrect): CT angiography is primarily used to evaluate arterial pathology or complex venous anatomy, such as May-Thurner syndrome, or for detailed staging of lymphedema. It is a more invasive test involving radiation and contrast, and generally not the initial investigation for undifferentiated bilateral non-pitting lower limb swelling, especially when venous causes are a primary concern.\nOption B (duplex ultrasound) (Correct): Duplex ultrasound is the appropriate initial investigation to rule out venous insufficiency or DVT, which can cause or contribute to lower limb swelling, even if non-pitting. While non-pitting edema is characteristic of lymphedema, venous pathology must first be excluded.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Pitting Edema                               | Non-Pitting Edema                                 | Investigation (Initial) | Investigation (Advanced) |\n|---------------------|---------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|-------------------------|--------------------------|\n| Common Causes       | DVT, CHF, Renal failure, Liver disease, CVI | Lymphedema, Myxedema, Lipedema, Chronic CVI       | Duplex Ultrasound       | Lymphoscintigraphy, CT/MRI |\n| Pathophysiology     | Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure    | Impaired lymphatic drainage, protein accumulation | Assess venous flow      | Assess lymphatic flow    |\n| Clinical Appearance | Indentation with pressure                   | No indentation with pressure, firm, brawny        | Rule out DVT/CVI        | Stage lymphedema         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-pitting edema? Rule out venous causes first with duplex ultrasound.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn duplex ultrasound, you would assess for deep vein thrombosis (presence of thrombus, non-compressibility of veins), venous reflux (prolonged retrograde flow after augmentation), and venous obstruction. In cases of lymphedema, the ultrasound might show subcutaneous fluid and thickened skin, but the venous system would typically be patent and competent.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Venous Forum (AVF) and the Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) guidelines recommend duplex ultrasound as the primary imaging modality for evaluating patients with suspected venous disease and lower extremity swelling.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | duplex ultrasound | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Key word: Non pitting edema = duplex Treat non pitting edema= if no swelling =bandage if swelling =l** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
