  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When legs swell without a pit, ultrasound's the first hit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duplex US. Unilateral non-pitting edema, skin thickening, and hyperpigmentation strongly suggest chronic venous insufficiency or lymphedema, and Duplex ultrasound is the most appropriate initial diagnostic step to evaluate the venous system and rule out other etiologies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-pitting edema, especially when chronic and associated with skin changes like thickening and hyperpigmentation (dermal fibrosis), points towards either advanced chronic venous disease or lymphedema. Duplex ultrasound is the gold standard for evaluating the venous system, allowing for the assessment of deep vein thrombosis (DVT), venous reflux, and venous obstruction. It is also crucial for ruling out other causes of leg swelling, such as popliteal cysts or masses that might cause lymphatic compression. Its non-invasive nature, accessibility, and ability to provide real-time dynamic information make it the ideal first-line investigation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT angiography) (Incorrect): CT angiography is primarily used to evaluate arterial pathology and is not the initial diagnostic step for non-pitting edema, which is typically venous or lymphatic in origin.\nOption B (MRV) (Incorrect): While MRV can evaluate venous anatomy, it is more expensive, less accessible, and generally not the initial imaging modality for leg edema when Duplex US can provide essential information about DVT and venous insufficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Indication | Utility in Non-Pitting Edema |\n|------------------|--------------------|-------------------------------|\n| Duplex US        | DVT, Venous Insufficiency | First-line; rules out venous causes, assesses tissue changes |\n| MRV              | Venous obstruction, complex anatomy | Second-line; for unclear US findings or central venous issues |\n| CT Angiography   | Arterial pathology | Not indicated for primary evaluation of non-pitting edema |\n| Lymphoscintigraphy | Lymphedema diagnosis | Confirmatory test for lymphedema, assesses lymphatic flow |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral non-pitting edema = Duplex US first to rule out venous causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Duplex US, you would assess for DVT (non-compressibility of veins, intraluminal thrombus), evaluate venous reflux (prolonged flow reversal with Valsalva or distal compression), and look for signs of chronic venous changes (dilated veins, skin thickening). It can also identify masses compressing lymphatic structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) clinical practice guidelines for the management of venous leg ulcers (2014) recommend Duplex ultrasound as the initial diagnostic test for patients with leg edema to assess for venous disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT angiography. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRV. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duplex US | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) (initial and the next) Key word: Non-Pitting edema is due to Lymphedema, Ultrasound is useful to exc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
