  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't trust a diabetic's pulse; trust the Duplex.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duplex of the affected leg. This is the best initial test because even with intact pulses, a diabetic patient with a non-healing ulcer requires objective assessment of arterial inflow to rule out peripheral arterial disease (PAD) as a contributing factor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuplex ultrasound is a non-invasive, readily available, and highly effective tool for evaluating arterial blood flow, identifying stenoses, and assessing the severity of PAD. In diabetic patients, palpable pulses can be misleading due to medial arterial calcification, which can falsely elevate ABI readings. Duplex directly visualizes the vessels and measures flow velocities, providing crucial information about the vascular supply to the ulcerated limb.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Douplex both legs) (Incorrect): While comparing both legs can be useful for comprehensive assessment or if bilateral symptoms are present, the question asks for the *best initial test* for the *affected* leg. A focused assessment is appropriate initially.\nOption C (CT angio) (Incorrect): CT angiography is a more invasive test involving radiation and contrast. It is typically reserved for surgical planning after non-invasive studies like Duplex ultrasound have identified significant pathology requiring intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Modality | Advantages | Disadvantages | Role in PAD |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Duplex Ultrasound | Non-invasive, sound waves | Real-time visualization, flow velocity, no radiation/contrast | Operator dependent, limited by calcification/obesity | Initial diagnostic, localization of stenosis |\n| CT Angiography | Invasive, X-rays with contrast | High resolution, 3D reconstruction, good for planning | Radiation, contrast nephrotoxicity, cost | Pre-operative planning, complex anatomy |\n| Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI) | Non-invasive, blood pressure cuffs | Simple, inexpensive, good screening tool | Falsely elevated in diabetics (calcification), less specific | Initial screening, but less reliable in diabetics |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always objectively assess arterial inflow in diabetic ulcers, even with palpable pulses.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Duplex ultrasound, you would look for areas of increased peak systolic velocity (PSV) indicating stenosis, spectral broadening, and dampened waveforms distal to stenoses or occlusions. The presence of monophasic waveforms or absence of flow would indicate severe disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Diabetic Foot (2023) recommends non-invasive vascular assessment, including Duplex ultrasound, for all diabetic foot ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Douplex  affected  leg | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Douplex both  legs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
