  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't treat the symptom, diagnose the disease, especially when two lives are at stake!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"complete evaluation\" because a pregnant patient presenting with hypertension and edema at 15 weeks gestation requires a thorough diagnostic workup to differentiate between various hypertensive disorders of pregnancy before initiating specific treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA complete evaluation is paramount to accurately diagnose the underlying cause of hypertension and edema in early pregnancy. This involves assessing for proteinuria, liver function abnormalities, thrombocytopenia, and renal dysfunction to distinguish between gestational hypertension, chronic hypertension, pre-eclampsia, or other secondary causes. Early and accurate diagnosis guides appropriate monitoring, risk stratification, and management strategies, which are crucial for both maternal and fetal well-being.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (atenolol) (Incorrect): Atenolol is contraindicated in pregnancy due to its association with fetal growth restriction, bradycardia, and other adverse effects. Beta-blockers like labetalol or nifedipine are generally preferred if antihypertensive medication is indicated, but only after a complete evaluation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Onset | Key Features | Management Principle |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gestational Hypertension | >20 weeks gestation | Hypertension without proteinuria | Close monitoring, consider delivery at term |\n| Chronic Hypertension | Before 20 weeks gestation or pre-existing | Hypertension before pregnancy or <20 weeks | Antihypertensives if severe, close monitoring |\n| Pre-eclampsia | >20 weeks gestation | Hypertension with proteinuria or end-organ dysfunction | Delivery is definitive treatment, symptom management |\n| Chronic HTN with Superimposed Pre-eclampsia | Before 20 weeks, then worsening | New onset proteinuria or worsening HTN/end-organ dysfunction | Similar to pre-eclampsia, often more severe |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always evaluate before treating, especially in complex physiological states like pregnancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile no specific imaging is indicated by the question, a complete evaluation might include a renal ultrasound if underlying kidney disease is suspected, or fetal ultrasound for growth and well-being assessment once a diagnosis is established.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 222: Hypertension in Pregnancy (2020). This guideline recommends a thorough evaluation for all pregnant patients presenting with hypertension to classify the disorder and guide management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | complete evaluation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | atenolol | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
