  "id": 203951,
  "question": "148-Pt  recent abdominal surgery presented by fever&otheres. what is the most cause? ![Image](/images/review_bank/515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx_8.jpg)",
  "options": {
    "A": "sepsis",
    "B": "subphrenic abscess"
  },
  "answer": "B) ✅ (Other names. Subdiaphragmatic Abscess. Specialty. Infectious disease, gastroenterology.                    Subphrenic abscess is a disease characterized by an accumulation of infected fluid between the \ndiaphragm, liver, and spleen.)",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let post-op fever linger; look for the hidden pus!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, subphrenic abscess. In a patient with recent abdominal surgery presenting with persistent fever and other symptoms, a localized collection of infected fluid like a subphrenic abscess is a common and critical cause of postoperative fever that requires specific intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPostoperative fever is a common and often benign occurrence, but persistent or high-grade fever, especially with other signs of infection, warrants investigation for surgical site infections or intra-abdominal collections. A subphrenic abscess, located in the space between the diaphragm and abdominal organs (liver/spleen), can result from contamination during surgery, an anastomotic leak, or inadequate drainage. Its location can make diagnosis challenging, as symptoms may be vague, but it often presents with fever, pleuritic pain, and sometimes shoulder tip pain due to diaphragmatic irritation. Prompt diagnosis and drainage are crucial to prevent further systemic complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sepsis is a systemic inflammatory response to infection, but it is a consequence or a broader syndrome, not the most specific *cause* of fever in this context. A subphrenic abscess is a specific localized infection that can *lead* to sepsis if untreated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Post-op Fever Cause | Typical Onset | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Atelectasis | Day 1-2 | Low-grade fever, hypoxemia, decreased breath sounds |\n| UTI | Day 3-5 | Dysuria, frequency, suprapubic pain, positive urine culture |\n| Wound Infection | Day 5-7 | Erythema, warmth, pain, purulent discharge at incision |\n| Intra-abdominal Abscess (e.g., Subphrenic) | Day 7-10+ | Persistent high fever, abdominal pain, leukocytosis, localized tenderness |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Persistent post-op fever + abdominal surgery = think abscess until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question includes an image tag, which would likely show an imaging modality. On CT scan, a subphrenic abscess typically appears as a well-defined, low-attenuation fluid collection with a rim-enhancing wall, often with gas bubbles. Ultrasound can also identify fluid collections, especially in the right upper quadrant. Intraoperatively, it would be a walled-off collection of purulent material in the subdiaphragmatic space.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSurgical Infection Society (SIS) Guidelines for the Management of Intra-abdominal Infection (2017) recommend prompt diagnosis and source control, typically percutaneous drainage, for intra-abdominal abscesses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sepsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | subphrenic abscess | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ✅ (Other names. Subdiaphragmatic Abscess. Specialty. Infectious disease, gastroenterology.          ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
