  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Honesty isn't just the best policy; it's the only policy in patient care.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. In the event of a retained surgical item, the immediate and paramount ethical responsibility of the surgeon is to apologize to the patient and fully disclose what happened, prioritizing transparency and patient trust.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis scenario highlights the critical importance of ethical principles in surgical practice, particularly patient autonomy, transparency, and professional responsibility. When a medical error, such as a retained surgical item (RSI), is discovered, the surgeon's primary duty is to inform the patient fully and truthfully about the error, its implications, and the corrective actions taken. This immediate and honest disclosure fosters trust, allows the patient to make informed decisions, and aligns with professional duties to uphold patient well-being and maintain the integrity of the medical profession.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Issuing a complaint against an assistant is an internal administrative process that does not address the immediate ethical obligation to the patient regarding the medical error.\nOption B (Incorrect): While legal counsel may be necessary at some point, the immediate and primary ethical obligation is to the patient, not to protect oneself legally before informing the patient. Patient disclosure takes precedence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Aspect of Medical Error Management | Immediate Patient Action | Internal/System Action | Legal/Professional Action |\n| :------------------------------- | :----------------------- | :--------------------- | :------------------------ |\n| **Priority**                     | Patient disclosure & care | Root cause analysis    | Legal counsel/reporting   |\n| **Goal**                         | Trust, informed consent  | Prevention, learning   | Compliance, defense       |\n| **Timing**                       | Immediate                | Promptly after patient care | As advised/required       |\n| **Key Principle**                | Transparency, empathy    | System improvement     | Accountability            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always disclose medical errors promptly and honestly to the patient.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a retained surgical gauze (gossypiboma) may appear as a well-circumscribed mass with a characteristic whorled or spongiform pattern, sometimes with gas bubbles or calcifications. Intraoperatively, a foreign body reaction or abscess may be encountered, with the gauze clearly visible upon exploration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Disclosure of Unanticipated Outcomes (2015) and The Joint Commission's Sentinel Event Policy (updated regularly) recommend prompt and honest disclosure of medical errors to patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Issue complaint against assistant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Call your lawyer and report the incident | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | apologize to the patient and tell her what happened | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ✅** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
