  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore blood in stool, especially in the elderly!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nRectal cancer is the correct answer. The combination of an old patient, new onset change in bowel habits (constipation on and off), and streaking of blood in the stool is highly suspicious for colorectal malignancy, with rectal cancer being a prime suspect given the distal bleeding pattern.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColorectal cancer is a disease predominantly affecting older individuals, and a change in bowel habits, such as alternating constipation, is a classic alarm symptom. Streaking of bright red blood in the stool is a common presentation for rectal lesions, as the blood is not mixed with stool for a prolonged period. Early rectal cancers may not cause pain or a sensation of fullness, making the absence of these symptoms unreliable for ruling out malignancy. The rectum is a common site for colorectal cancer development.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Sigmoid cancer): Incorrect. While sigmoid cancer can cause changes in bowel habits and bleeding, streaking of blood is more characteristic of a more distal lesion like rectal cancer. Sigmoid lesions are more likely to cause occult bleeding or melena if bleeding is significant.\nOption C (chronic hemorrhoid): Incorrect. While chronic hemorrhoids cause streaking of bright red blood, they typically do not explain a new onset change in bowel habits like 'constipation on and off' in an elderly patient. Any new rectal bleeding in an older individual warrants investigation for malignancy, even if hemorrhoids are present.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Rectal Cancer | Sigmoid Cancer | Chronic Hemorrhoids |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Typical Patient** | Older adult | Older adult | Any age, often associated with straining |\n| **Bowel Habits** | Change in bowel habits (constipation/diarrhea), tenesmus | Change in bowel habits, obstruction | Usually normal, can worsen with constipation |\n| **Bleeding** | Streaking of blood, bright red blood, often mixed with stool | Occult blood, melena, dark red blood, change in stool caliber | Bright red blood, typically on toilet paper or dripping after defecation, not usually mixed with stool |\n| **Pain/Fullness** | May be absent early, tenesmus later | Abdominal pain, distension, obstruction | Perianal discomfort, itching, pain with thrombosis |\n| **Diagnostic Priority** | Colonoscopy/Proctoscopy | Colonoscopy | Anoscopy, clinical exam (but rule out malignancy first in elderly) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New onset rectal bleeding in an old patient = cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy (proctoscopy/colonoscopy) would reveal an exophytic, friable, or ulcerated mass in the rectum. Biopsy would confirm adenocarcinoma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Rectal Cancer (2024). Recommends colonoscopy for any new onset rectal bleeding or change in bowel habits in patients over 45, or younger with risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sigmoid cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | rectal cancer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | chronic hemorrhoid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) old age** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
