  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sclerotherapy: Internal affairs only, keep it above the line!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Internal hemorrhoids. Sclerotherapy is a well-established, minimally invasive treatment specifically designed for internal hemorrhoids, aiming to reduce their size and symptoms by inducing fibrosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSclerotherapy involves injecting a chemical irritant (sclerosant) into the submucosal tissue at the base of the internal hemorrhoid, typically above the dentate line. This injection causes an inflammatory reaction, leading to fibrosis and scarring, which fixes the hemorrhoidal tissue to the underlying muscular wall and reduces its vascularity. The procedure is effective for bleeding and mild prolapse of Grade I and II internal hemorrhoids, leveraging the pain-insensitive nature of the columnar epithelium above the dentate line.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): External hemorrhoids are located distal to the dentate line and are covered by pain-sensitive anoderm. Sclerotherapy is contraindicated for external hemorrhoids due to the risk of severe pain, tissue necrosis, and skin sloughing.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Internal Hemorrhoids | External Hemorrhoids |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Proximal to dentate line | Distal to dentate line |\n| **Covering** | Columnar epithelium (pain-insensitive) | Anoderm (pain-sensitive) |\n| **Primary Symptoms** | Painless bleeding, prolapse | Pain, thrombosis, swelling |\n| **Sclerotherapy** | Indicated (Grade I/II) | Contraindicated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sclerotherapy targets internal hemorrhoids, above the dentate line, for fibrosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring anoscopy, internal hemorrhoids appear as vascular cushions covered by a reddish-pink mucosa. Sclerotherapy involves direct injection into the submucosa at the apex of these cushions, typically at the 3, 7, and 11 o'clock positions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018) recommends sclerotherapy as a first-line treatment for symptomatic Grade I and II internal hemorrhoids.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Internal hemorrhoids | ✅ Correct |\n| B | External hemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) سكليروا = سكين = لازم يدخل جوه = internal** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
