  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut the internal, save the external; heal the fissure, keep the control.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: This question correctly identifies Lateral Internal Sphincterotomy (LIS) as the definitive surgical treatment for chronic anal fissures, especially when complicated by a sentinel pile and failed medical management. LIS addresses the underlying hypertonicity of the internal anal sphincter, which is the primary driver of chronic fissure formation and non-healing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic anal fissures are often caused by hypertonicity of the internal anal sphincter, leading to ischemia and impaired healing. LIS involves a controlled division of a portion of the internal anal sphincter, typically in the lateral position, to reduce this hypertonicity. This decreases anal canal pressure, improves blood supply to the anoderm, and facilitates fissure healing. The internal anal sphincter is an involuntary smooth muscle, making its partial division effective without compromising continence significantly, unlike the external sphincter.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lateral external sphincterotomy. The external anal sphincter is a voluntary skeletal muscle crucial for continence. Dividing it would lead to severe fecal incontinence, which is an unacceptable complication for anal fissure treatment. The pathology of anal fissure primarily involves the internal, involuntary sphincter.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Internal Anal Sphincter | External Anal Sphincter | Lateral Internal Sphincterotomy (LIS) | Fissurectomy (with LIS) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Muscle Type | Smooth (involuntary) | Skeletal (voluntary) | Surgical division of internal sphincter | Excision of fissure, often with LIS |\n| Primary Function | Resting tone, maintains continence at rest | Voluntary squeeze, maintains continence during stress | Reduces hypertonicity, promotes healing of chronic fissure | Removes fibrotic tissue, promotes healing, may be combined with LIS |\n| Role in Anal Fissure | Hypertonicity causes ischemia, prevents healing | Not directly involved in fissure pathophysiology | Definitive treatment for chronic fissure, high success rate | For very chronic, fibrotic, or non-healing fissures |\n| Risk of Incontinence | Low with partial division | High with division | Low risk of minor incontinence (flatus/soiling) | Similar to LIS, potentially slightly higher if extensive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Internal sphincter for internal problem (fissure).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a chronic anal fissure typically appears as a deep ulcer in the posterior midline (less commonly anterior), often with hypertrophied skin tags (sentinel pile) distally and an enlarged anal papilla proximally. During LIS, the intersphincteric groove is identified, and a small incision is made to expose and divide a portion of the internal anal sphincter muscle fibers, usually 3-5mm in length, while carefully preserving the external sphincter.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anal Fissure (2017/2023 update) recommend LIS as the gold standard surgical treatment for chronic anal fissures refractory to medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | _Lateral external sphincterotomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | _ Lateral internal sphincterotomy(LIS) | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ربط = ( Anal = internal ) حرف n مع n .\nLateral internal sphincterotomy is an operation performed on ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
