  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just watch the fever; find the fire within!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, CT abdomen. A patient with a spiking fever one week post-resection and colostomy, despite clear external exams, strongly suggests an intra-abdominal complication requiring immediate investigation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSpiking fever in the post-operative period, particularly after gastrointestinal surgery, is a red flag for serious intra-abdominal pathology such as an anastomotic leak, abscess formation, or peritonitis. While superficial signs may be absent, deep-seated infections or leaks can manifest solely as systemic inflammatory response. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast is the gold standard for identifying these complications, providing detailed anatomical information crucial for diagnosis and guiding further intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Reassuring a patient with a spiking fever one week post-op after bowel surgery is inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Spiking fever is a significant sign of an underlying complication that requires investigation, not dismissal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Post-op Fever Etiology | Typical Onset | Key Features | Initial Workup |\n| :--------------------- | :------------ | :----------- | :------------- |\n| **Wind** (Atelectasis/Pneumonia) | Day 1-2 | Hypoxia, cough, crackles | CXR, sputum culture |\n| **Water** (UTI) | Day 3-5 | Dysuria, frequency, suprapubic pain | Urinalysis, urine culture |\n| **Wound** (SSI) | Day 5-7 | Erythema, warmth, purulent drainage | Wound inspection, culture |\n| **Walk** (DVT/PE) | Day 5-10 | Leg swelling/pain, dyspnea, tachycardia | Duplex US, CT PE protocol |\n| **What did we do?** (Abscess/Leak) | Day 5-10+ | Spiking fever, abdominal pain, ileus | CT Abdomen/Pelvis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Spiking fever post-op after bowel surgery demands intra-abdominal imaging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT abdomen with IV contrast would likely reveal an intra-abdominal fluid collection, abscess, anastomotic leak (extravasation of contrast), or signs of peritonitis (fat stranding, free fluid).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Anastomotic Leak in Gastrointestinal Surgery 2021: These guidelines emphasize early diagnosis and intervention for anastomotic leaks, often recommending CT imaging as the primary diagnostic tool for suspected intra-abdominal complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT abdomen | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Reassure | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Key word: spiking fever there is sings in peritonitis problem = ct** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
