  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut until you know where it's spread!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct next step after diagnosing invasive gastric adenocarcinoma is to perform comprehensive staging with a CT scan of the abdomen, chest, and pelvis. This is crucial to determine the extent of disease spread, particularly for distant metastases, which dictates resectability and treatment strategy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFollowing a diagnosis of invasive gastric adenocarcinoma, accurate staging is paramount to guide appropriate management. A CT scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis is the gold standard for detecting distant metastatic disease (M stage), such as liver metastases, peritoneal carcinomatosis, or lung involvement. It also provides valuable information on regional lymph node involvement and local tumor extent. This comprehensive assessment is critical for deciding between curative surgical resection, neoadjuvant therapy, or palliative care, ensuring the patient receives the most appropriate and effective treatment plan.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is excellent for local T and N staging (depth of invasion and regional lymph nodes) but is inadequate for detecting distant metastases.\nOption C (Incorrect): Abdominal ultrasound has limited utility in comprehensive staging of gastric cancer due to poor visualization of the stomach wall and its inability to reliably detect distant metastases or peritoneal spread.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Staging Modality | Primary Role | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|\n| **CT Chest/Abdomen/Pelvis** | Detects distant metastases (M stage), assesses regional nodes (N), and local tumor extent (T). | Less accurate for T-staging than EUS; can miss microscopic peritoneal disease. |\n| **Endoscopic Ultrasound (EUS)** | Highly accurate for local T-staging (depth of invasion) and regional N-staging. | Cannot detect distant metastases. |\n| **Diagnostic Laparoscopy** | Detects occult peritoneal metastases not seen on CT, obtains peritoneal washings. | Invasive; not always necessary if clear distant mets on CT. |\n| **PET-CT** | Detects distant metastases, especially in poorly differentiated tumors; assesses response to neoadjuvant therapy. | Not routinely recommended for all gastric cancers; can have false positives. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric cancer staging starts with comprehensive CT to rule out distant mets.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, gastric adenocarcinoma may appear as focal or diffuse wall thickening, often with enhancement. Look for liver lesions, ascites, omental caking, enlarged retroperitoneal or supraclavicular lymph nodes, and lung nodules, all indicative of metastatic disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023). These guidelines recommend comprehensive cross-sectional imaging (CT chest/abdomen/pelvis) as a primary staging modality for gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | endoscopic US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT abdomen and chest and pelvis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | abdominal US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) عشان اشوف الورم انتشر لا لا** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
