  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For chronic clots, V/Q scan is your best shot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, QV ratio, which refers to the Ventilation-Perfusion (V/Q) scan. A V/Q scan is the gold standard screening test for chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH) due to its high sensitivity for detecting perfusion defects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCTEPH results from incomplete resolution of acute pulmonary emboli, leading to chronic obstruction of pulmonary arteries. A V/Q scan assesses regional ventilation (V) and perfusion (Q) of the lungs. In CTEPH, characteristic findings include areas of normal ventilation but absent or significantly reduced perfusion (V/Q mismatch) due to organized, chronic thrombi. This specific pattern of mismatch is highly suggestive of CTEPH and guides further diagnostic workup.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (spiral CT) (Incorrect): While CT pulmonary angiography (CTPA) is excellent for diagnosing acute pulmonary embolism, its sensitivity for detecting chronic, organized thrombi in CTEPH can be lower, especially for smaller, peripheral lesions. It is often used for surgical planning after a V/Q scan suggests CTEPH, but not as the primary screening tool.\nOption C (D dimer) (Incorrect): D-dimer is a fibrin degradation product primarily used to rule out acute pulmonary embolism due to its high negative predictive value. It is often elevated in CTEPH but is non-specific and cannot confirm the diagnosis or localize the chronic thrombi, making it unsuitable for confirming chronic thromboembolism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Tool | Primary Use | Findings in CTEPH |\n|---|---|---|\n| V/Q Scan | Screening for CTEPH | Mismatched defects (normal ventilation, abnormal perfusion) |\n| CTPA | Acute PE diagnosis, surgical planning | May show organized thrombi, webs, stenoses, or recanalization |\n| D-dimer | Rule out acute PE | Often elevated, non-specific, not diagnostic for chronic disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: V/Q scan is the gold standard screening for CTEPH.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a V/Q scan, CTEPH typically presents as segmental or subsegmental perfusion defects with preserved ventilation. CT pulmonary angiography (CTPA) may reveal direct signs such as organized thrombi, webs, bands, or stenoses within the pulmonary arteries, or indirect signs like mosaic perfusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2022 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension: Recommend V/Q scan as the initial screening test for CTEPH in all patients with unexplained pulmonary hypertension.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | QV ratio | ✅ Correct |\n| B | spiral CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | D dimer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
