  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, image it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with acute hemiparesis following a procedure, and has a history of diabetes. The correct answer, CT angiography, is crucial for rapidly diagnosing the underlying cause of the neurological deficit, which is highly suggestive of a stroke (ischemic or hemorrhagic) in this context.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute hemiparesis necessitates immediate neuroimaging to differentiate between ischemic and hemorrhagic stroke. In a diabetic patient post-procedure, there's an increased risk of both thrombotic events (ischemic stroke) and potential complications leading to hemorrhage. CT angiography provides rapid visualization of cerebral vasculature, allowing for the identification of large vessel occlusions amenable to thrombectomy, or ruling out hemorrhage, which is critical before considering thrombolytic therapy like tPA. The ability to assess blood vessels for thrombosis or hemorrhage is paramount in guiding acute management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (tpA) (Incorrect): Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) is a thrombolytic agent used to treat acute ischemic stroke, but it is a treatment, not a diagnostic tool. Administering tPA without first ruling out hemorrhagic stroke via imaging is absolutely contraindicated and could be fatal.\nOption B (Warfarin) (Incorrect): Warfarin is an an anticoagulant used for long-term stroke prevention in certain conditions (e.g., atrial fibrillation) or for treating thrombotic events. It is a treatment, not a diagnostic, and would be contraindicated in acute hemorrhagic stroke.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Use in Acute Stroke | Key Findings |\n| :--------------- | :-------------------------- | :----------- |\n| Non-contrast CT | Initial rapid assessment | Rules out hemorrhage; early ischemic changes (subtle) |\n| CT Angiography | Vascular assessment | Identifies large vessel occlusion, aneurysms, dissections |\n| CT Perfusion | Tissue viability | Assesses penumbra (at-risk tissue) |\n| MRI Brain | Detailed parenchymal imaging | More sensitive for early ischemia, posterior fossa, small strokes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute hemiparesis post-procedure in a diabetic? Image first to rule out hemorrhage and assess vessels.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, an ischemic stroke due to large vessel occlusion would appear as a filling defect or abrupt cut-off in a cerebral artery. A hemorrhagic stroke would show extravasated contrast if actively bleeding, or simply hyperdense blood on the initial non-contrast CT.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association/American Stroke Association (AHA/ASA) Guidelines for the Early Management of Patients with Acute Ischemic Stroke (e.g., 2019/2024) recommend immediate non-contrast CT brain to rule out hemorrhage, followed by CT angiography for large vessel occlusion assessment in eligible patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | tpA | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Warfarin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ct angio | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) احتمال يكون جاه strok لان قال عمل بروسيجر فممكن سار له ارتفاع شديد بالسكر واثر على small vessl brain** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
