  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-sleeve pain? CT with contrast is your leak detector!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT with contrast. Abdominal pain three weeks after sleeve gastrectomy is a red flag for a potential leak or perforation, and CT with contrast is the gold standard diagnostic imaging modality for these serious complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSleeve gastrectomy involves creating a long staple line along the greater curvature of the stomach. Leaks or perforations, often occurring at the gastroesophageal junction or angle of His, can lead to peritonitis or abscess formation. CT with oral and/or intravenous contrast allows for direct visualization of contrast extravasation from the staple line, identification of perigastric fluid collections, and detection of free air, all indicative of a leak or perforation. This comprehensive view is crucial for timely diagnosis and intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption 1 (US) (Incorrect): Ultrasound has limited utility in diagnosing gastric leaks or perforations due to interference from bowel gas and its inability to reliably detect small extravasations or retroperitoneal fluid collections.\nOption 3 (Plain abdominal X Ray) (Incorrect): While a plain X-ray can show free air if a perforation is significant, it is insensitive for small or contained leaks and cannot demonstrate contrast extravasation, making it inadequate as a primary diagnostic tool for this specific complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Modality | Primary Use in Post-Sleeve Pain | Sensitivity for Leak | Radiation Exposure |\n|--------------------|---------------------------------|----------------------|--------------------|\n| CT with Contrast   | Gold standard for leak/abscess  | High                 | Moderate-High      |\n| Upper GI Series    | Alternative for leak, anatomy   | Moderate-High        | Moderate           |\n| Ultrasound         | Abscess, fluid collections      | Low                  | None               |\n| Plain X-ray        | Free air (gross perforation)    | Low                  | Low                |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-sleeve gastrectomy pain demands CT with contrast to rule out leak.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT with oral contrast, a leak would appear as extravasation of contrast material from the gastric staple line into the peritoneal cavity or a contained fluid collection. Other findings might include perigastric inflammatory changes, free fluid, or free air.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASMBS (American Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery) Guidelines for the Perioperative Nutritional, Metabolic, and Nonsurgical Support of Patients Undergoing Bariatric Surgery (2019) recommend prompt imaging, often CT with oral contrast, for suspected anastomotic or staple line leaks.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| 1 | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| 2 | CT with contrast | ✅ Correct |\n| 3 | Plain abdominal X Ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: 2) Key word: diagnostic CT for perforation** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
