  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spleen preservation: a stable patient's best friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is splenic conservative surgery. This question describes a Grade III splenic injury (4 cm tear, 7 cm hematoma), which, in a hemodynamically stable patient, is typically managed with non-operative management or splenic preservation techniques to avoid the long-term complications of splenectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic conservative surgery, encompassing non-operative management (NOM), splenorrhaphy, partial splenectomy, or angioembolization, is the preferred approach for most splenic injuries, including Grade III, in stable patients. The spleen plays a crucial role in immune function, particularly against encapsulated bacteria, and its preservation significantly reduces the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI). Advances in imaging, critical care, and interventional radiology have made NOM highly successful, with success rates exceeding 90% for lower-grade injuries and still high for Grade III injuries in stable patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (splenectomy) (Incorrect): Splenectomy is reserved for hemodynamically unstable patients, those with ongoing bleeding despite conservative measures, or extensive splenic destruction (Grade IV/V) where preservation is not feasible. It carries significant long-term risks including OPSI, thrombocytosis, and increased cardiovascular risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Splenic Injury Grade (AAST) | Description | Management in Stable Patient |\n|---|---|---|\n| I | Subcapsular hematoma <10% surface area; Laceration <1 cm deep | Non-operative management (NOM) |\n| II | Subcapsular hematoma 10-50% surface area; Laceration 1-3 cm deep | NOM |\n| III | Subcapsular hematoma >50% or expanding; Intraparenchymal hematoma >5 cm or expanding; Laceration >3 cm deep | NOM (consider angioembolization) or Splenic Preservation |\n| IV | Laceration involving segmental/hilar vessels with major devascularization (>25%); Ruptured intraparenchymal hematoma | NOM (often with angioembolization) or Splenectomy |\n| V | Shattered spleen; Hilar vascular injury with devascularization | Splenectomy (often) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Preserve the spleen whenever possible in stable trauma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a Grade III injury would show a deep laceration (>3 cm) and/or a large intraparenchymal hematoma (>5 cm or >50% surface area). Intraoperatively, this would appear as a significant tear with associated bleeding, but potentially amenable to repair or partial resection if the patient is stable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Splenic Injury Scale (1994, revised). Recommends non-operative management for most splenic injuries (Grades I-III, and even some IV) in hemodynamically stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | splenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | splenic conservative surgery | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
