  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the post-op fever hits early, check the pee, not just the spleen.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is UTI. In the early postoperative period (days 1-5), fever is a common occurrence, and urinary tract infections are a leading cause, often linked to indwelling urinary catheters.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPostoperative fever etiology is often time-dependent. UTIs frequently manifest within the first 3-5 days due to the common use of urinary catheters during surgery, which can introduce bacteria and lead to ascending infections. Immobility and altered bladder dynamics post-surgery can further contribute to urinary stasis, increasing the risk of infection. While other causes like atelectasis can cause early fever, UTI is a more common cause of bacteremia in this timeframe.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Peritoneal transfer) (Incorrect): \"Peritoneal transfer\" is not a recognized medical term for a cause of bacteremia or fever. While intra-abdominal contamination can lead to peritonitis or abscess, this would be termed an intra-abdominal infection, not \"peritoneal transfer,\" and would typically present with more localized abdominal signs in addition to fever. A UTI is a far more common and earlier cause of isolated fever post-surgery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Post-op Day | Common Causes of Fever | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Day 1-2 | Atelectasis, Dehydration, UTI | Mild fever, cough (atelectasis), concentrated urine (dehydration), dysuria (UTI) |\n| Day 3-5 | UTI, Pneumonia, Wound Infection | Dysuria/frequency (UTI), cough/sputum (pneumonia), erythema/pain at incision (wound) |\n| Day 5-7+ | Wound Infection, Abscess, DVT, Drug Fever | Localized signs (wound/abscess), leg swelling/pain (DVT), fever without clear source (drug) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The 5 W's of post-op fever: Wind, Water, Wound, Walk, Wonder drugs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor suspected UTI, a urinalysis and urine culture are the primary diagnostic tools. Imaging like CT or ultrasound is generally not indicated for uncomplicated post-splenectomy fever unless there are signs of intra-abdominal collection or other specific complications. Intraoperatively during splenectomy, meticulous hemostasis and careful handling of surrounding organs are crucial to prevent future complications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGuidelines for the Prevention of Catheter-Associated Urinary Tract Infections, CDC 2009 (updated 2014). These guidelines recommend avoiding unnecessary catheterization and prompt removal when no longer needed.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | UTI | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Peritoneal transfer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Key word: fever day 3-5 post op is UTI.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
