  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pubic tubercle: your compass for hernia type.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Femoral hernia. This is a classic presentation, as femoral hernias are anatomically defined by their location inferior and lateral to the pubic tubercle, a key landmark for differentiating them from inguinal hernias.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFemoral hernias occur when abdominal contents protrude through the femoral canal, an anatomical space bounded superiorly by the inguinal ligament, medially by the lacunar ligament, posteriorly by the pectineal ligament, and laterally by the femoral vein. This narrow neck makes femoral hernias particularly susceptible to incarceration and strangulation, necessitating prompt diagnosis and repair. The pubic tubercle serves as a critical anatomical reference point; hernias superior and medial to it are typically inguinal, while those inferior and lateral are femoral.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Obturator hernias are rare and protrude through the obturator canal, typically presenting with pain along the medial thigh (Howship-Romberg sign) due to obturator nerve compression. Their location is deep within the pelvis, not superficial and inferior/lateral to the pubic tubercle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Inguinal Hernia | Femoral Hernia | Obturator Hernia |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location relative to Pubic Tubercle** | Superior and medial | Inferior and lateral | Deep in obturator canal |\n| **Sex Predominance** | Males | Females | Elderly, emaciated females |\n| **Risk of Strangulation** | Moderate | High | High |\n| **Presentation** | Groin bulge, often reducible | Groin bulge, often irreducible | Medial thigh pain (Howship-Romberg sign) |\n| **Anatomical Passage** | Inguinal canal | Femoral canal | Obturator canal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Inferior and lateral to pubic tubercle? Think Femoral.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a femoral hernia appears as a fat-containing sac or bowel loop inferior to the inguinal ligament and lateral to the pubic tubercle, often medial to the femoral vein. Intraoperatively, it is identified by dissecting below the inguinal ligament, medial to the femoral vein, and lateral to the lacunar ligament.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Hernia Society (EHS) Guidelines on the Treatment of Inguinal Hernia (2018) recommend careful clinical examination for hernia diagnosis, emphasizing anatomical landmarks for differentiation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Femoral | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Obturator. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ( InFerior = Femoral ربط (** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
