  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it wiggles and squishes, it's probably a cyst, not a crisis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Sebaceous cyst. The positive fluctuating test is the critical clue, indicating a fluid or semi-fluid filled lesion, which is characteristic of a sebaceous cyst containing keratinous material.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSebaceous cysts, more accurately termed epidermoid cysts, arise from obstructed pilosebaceous ducts, leading to the accumulation of keratin and sebum within an epithelial-lined sac. This material, often semi-liquid or pasty, gives the cyst its characteristic fluctuant feel on palpation. While common on the head and neck, they can occur anywhere on the body, including the thigh, and typically present as mobile, painless lumps with normal overlying skin until infected.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lipomas are soft, mobile, and rubbery, but typically do not exhibit fluctuation as they are composed of solid fatty tissue.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sarcomas are malignant tumors, usually firm, fixed, and rapidly growing. While some may undergo necrosis and become soft, fluctuation is not their primary distinguishing feature.\nOption C (Incorrect): An aneurysm is a vascular lesion that would present with pulsatility, not just fluctuation, and often a thrill or bruit, which are not mentioned.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sebaceous Cyst (Epidermoid) | Lipoma | Sarcoma | Aneurysm |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Consistency** | Fluctuant, firm (if tense) | Soft, rubbery | Firm, hard | Pulsatile, compressible |\n| **Pulsatility** | No | No | No | Yes |\n| **Mobility** | Mobile | Mobile | Fixed (often) | Mobile with vessel |\n| **Growth** | Slow | Slow | Rapid | Variable |\n| **Malignancy** | Benign | Benign | Malignant | Benign (vascular) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fluctuant lump? Think fluid-filled, like a sebaceous cyst or abscess.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a sebaceous cyst appears as a well-circumscribed, anechoic or hypoechoic lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement, often containing internal echoes representing keratin debris. Intraoperatively, it appears as a white or yellowish encapsulated sac filled with cheesy, malodorous material.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for management of benign skin lesions (e.g., 2019) recommend surgical excision for symptomatic or cosmetically bothersome epidermoid cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Aneurysm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sebaceous cyst | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Key word\n:=sebaceous cyst low- growing ,mobile , firm, painless nodule , dark colored may be seen on** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
