  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When secretin says 'go,' gastrinoma's the foe!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct answer is Gastrinoma. The constellation of epigastric pain, diarrhea, and peptic ulcers, coupled with a positive secretin stimulation test, is pathognomonic for Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome (ZES) caused by a gastrinoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrinomas are neuroendocrine tumors that autonomously secrete excessive amounts of gastrin. This hypergastrinemia leads to profound gastric acid hypersecretion, causing severe and often refractory peptic ulcer disease, typically in unusual locations. The high acid load also overwhelms pancreatic bicarbonate, inactivating pancreatic enzymes and damaging the intestinal mucosa, resulting in malabsorption and secretory diarrhea. The secretin stimulation test is diagnostic because, unlike normal G cells which are inhibited by secretin, gastrinoma cells paradoxically release more gastrin in response to secretin.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Carcinoid) (Incorrect): Carcinoid tumors produce serotonin and other vasoactive peptides, leading to carcinoid syndrome characterized by flushing, diarrhea, and bronchospasm. They do not typically cause peptic ulcers or respond to a secretin stimulation test in this manner.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome) | Carcinoid Syndrome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Hormone | Gastrin | Serotonin, Substance P, Bradykinin |\n| Key Symptoms | Severe peptic ulcers, diarrhea, abdominal pain | Flushing, diarrhea, bronchospasm, valvular heart disease |\n| Diagnostic Test | Secretin stimulation test (positive) | 24-hour urinary 5-HIAA, Chromogranin A |\n| Tumor Location | Pancreas, duodenum | GI tract (esp. small bowel), lung, appendix |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Secretin test positive + ulcers = Gastrinoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for gastrinoma often involves somatostatin receptor scintigraphy (SRS or Octreoscan) to localize the primary tumor and metastases, as well as endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) for pancreatic/duodenal lesions. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the duodenum and pancreas is crucial, and sometimes intraoperative ultrasound is used to identify small tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Gastrinoma (2017) recommend biochemical confirmation with fasting gastrin levels and secretin stimulation test, followed by imaging for localization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Carcinoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
