  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't give Bupropion if their brain does the electric slide!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Bupropion is unequivocally contraindicated in patients with a history of epilepsy because it significantly lowers the seizure threshold, thereby increasing the risk of seizure recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBupropion is an atypical antidepressant that functions as a norepinephrine-dopamine reuptake inhibitor (NDRI). While highly effective for smoking cessation and depression, its pharmacological action, particularly its dopaminergic and noradrenergic effects, can disrupt normal neuronal excitability. This leads to a dose-dependent reduction in the seizure threshold, making it unsafe for individuals with pre-existing seizure disorders or other conditions that predispose to seizures, such as anorexia nervosa or bulimia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Nicotine replacement medication (NRT) is a safe and effective first-line treatment for smoking cessation in most patients, including those with epilepsy. It does not significantly alter the seizure threshold and is not contraindicated in this patient population.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Smoking Cessation Aid | Mechanism of Action | Key Contraindications | Common Side Effects |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nicotine Replacement Therapy (NRT) | Replaces nicotine, reduces withdrawal symptoms | Unstable cardiovascular disease (acute MI, severe arrhythmia) | Nausea, headache, insomnia, local irritation |\n| Bupropion | Norepinephrine-dopamine reuptake inhibitor (NDRI) | Seizure disorder, anorexia/bulimia, abrupt alcohol/sedative withdrawal | Seizures, dry mouth, insomnia, agitation |\n| Varenicline | Partial nicotinic acetylcholine receptor agonist | Severe renal impairment (dose adjustment), neuropsychiatric events (caution) | Nausea, insomnia, abnormal dreams, neuropsychiatric symptoms |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bupropion lowers seizure threshold; avoid in epilepsy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2008 PHS Clinical Practice Guideline: Treating Tobacco Use and Dependence recommends Bupropion as a first-line pharmacotherapy but explicitly contraindicates its use in patients with a history of seizure disorders.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | _ nicotine replacement medication | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | _ Bupropion = epilepsy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
