  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut out the cortisol, cure the Cushing's.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Surgical resection. An adrenal tumor causing high cortisol symptoms (Cushing's syndrome) is best managed by surgical removal of the affected adrenal gland, as this is the definitive treatment to eliminate the source of excess hormone production.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUnilateral adrenal adenomas or carcinomas causing Cushing's syndrome are primarily treated with adrenalectomy. This procedure, often performed laparoscopically, directly removes the hypersecreting gland, leading to biochemical cure and resolution of Cushingoid features. Preoperative preparation, including exclusion of pheochromocytoma and, in severe cases, cortisol-lowering agents, is crucial for patient safety and optimal outcomes. The goal is to normalize cortisol levels and reverse the systemic effects of hypercortisolism.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Chemotherapy): Incorrect. Chemotherapy is generally reserved for metastatic adrenal cortical carcinoma, not for primary management of a localized cortisol-producing adrenal tumor.\nOption C (Radiation): Incorrect. Radiation therapy has a limited role in adrenal cortical carcinoma, primarily for palliation of metastatic disease or local recurrence, not as primary treatment for a resectable cortisol-producing tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Tumor Type | Hormone Production | Primary Treatment |\n| :----------------- | :----------------- | :---------------- |\n| Cortisol-producing Adenoma | Cortisol | Adrenalectomy |\n| Aldosterone-producing Adenoma | Aldosterone | Adrenalectomy |\n| Pheochromocytoma | Catecholamines | Adrenalectomy (after alpha-blockade) |\n| Adrenal Cortical Carcinoma | Variable (cortisol, androgens, aldosterone) | Adrenalectomy (if resectable) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adrenal hyperfunction from a tumor = surgical resection is often curative.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a cortisol-producing adrenal adenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, homogeneous mass, often with low attenuation. Intraoperatively, the tumor is identified within the adrenal gland, which is carefully dissected from surrounding retroperitoneal structures, often via a laparoscopic approach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Cushing's Syndrome (2021) recommends surgical resection as the primary treatment for adrenal adenomas causing Cushing's syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical resectio | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
