  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For early gastric cancer, less is more when it comes to resection.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. For cancer in the body of the stomach with no metastasis and no lymph node involvement, wide local excision with clear margins is the correct approach because it offers curative intent while preserving gastric function, appropriate for early-stage, highly localized disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWide local excision is a cornerstone of oncologic surgery for early-stage cancers, particularly when depth of invasion is limited and there's no evidence of regional or distant spread. This approach prioritizes organ preservation and minimizes surgical morbidity compared to a total or subtotal gastrectomy. The goal is to achieve R0 resection (microscopically clear margins) while maintaining quality of life, which is feasible for very early, superficial gastric cancers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (gastrectomy) (Incorrect): Gastrectomy, whether subtotal or total, is a more extensive procedure typically reserved for more advanced gastric cancers, those with deeper invasion, lymph node involvement, or larger tumor size. Performing a gastrectomy for a very early, localized, node-negative lesion would be overtreatment, leading to unnecessary morbidity and compromised quality of life.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage/Extent | Characteristics | Recommended Surgical Approach |\n| :----------- | :-------------- | :---------------------------- |\n| Early, Localized | No metastasis, no lymph node involvement, limited depth | Wide Local Excision (or Endoscopic Resection if superficial) |\n| Locally Advanced | Deeper invasion, regional lymph node involvement | Gastrectomy (subtotal/total) with lymphadenectomy |\n| Metastatic | Distant metastasis | Palliative (chemotherapy, bypass, stenting) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: No mets, no nodes = preserve stomach.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, an early gastric cancer might appear as a subtle mucosal irregularity, erosion, or small polypoid lesion. Intraoperatively, after careful palpation and visualization, the lesion would be confined to the gastric wall without palpable lymphadenopathy or serosal involvement. No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023). These guidelines recommend endoscopic resection or limited surgical resection for very early-stage, localized gastric cancers without lymph node involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | wide local local excision with clear margins | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Key word:\n no metastasis \nChest tube:\nHemthorax\n =\nblood accumulation in the lung ttt with chest tub** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
