  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut what doesn't grow or glow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'Observer'. This question highlights the importance of clinical judgment in managing stable, long-standing skin lesions, especially in a young patient, where observation is often the most appropriate initial approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFor skin lesions present since childhood and without any reported changes, the default management is observation. Surgical intervention, whether excision or ablation, is typically reserved for specific indications. Excision is indicated for lesions showing suspicious changes (e.g., growth, irregular borders, color changes) suggestive of malignancy, or for symptomatic lesions. Ablation (e.g., laser) is primarily for cosmetic concerns. Without these specific indications, unnecessary intervention should be avoided, adhering to the principle of 'first, do no harm'.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Laser - Excision) (Incorrect): Laser ablation or surgical excision would only be indicated if there were cosmetic concerns or signs of malignancy/growth, respectively. The question does not provide any of these indications, making observation the more prudent initial step.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion Characteristic | Indication for Intervention | Management Strategy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stable, benign-appearing, long-standing | None (unless patient request) | Observe |\n| Suspicious changes (growth, asymmetry, color change) | Potential malignancy | Excision (biopsy/definitive treatment) |\n| Cosmetically bothersome, benign | Patient desire for removal | Ablation (laser, cryo) or Excision |\n| Symptomatic (e.g., bleeding, itching) | Symptom relief | Excision or other targeted therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Observe stable, long-standing lesions; intervene for change or concern.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, one would observe a stable, non-changing skin lesion. If biopsied, histology would confirm a benign diagnosis (e.g., nevus, hemangioma, epidermal nevus) without features of malignancy or significant dysplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines for the Management of Melanoma (2019): Recommends regular skin self-exams and professional skin exams for individuals at risk, emphasizing observation for stable benign lesions and biopsy for suspicious ones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Laser -Excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Observer | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Key word:\n if cosmetic = ablation \nIf increase = excision** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
