  "answer": "C) كلهم صح لكن اكثر شيء يطون سبب في Ileus شلل الامعاء = low k Key word : you shod check K before and after operation the most common problem of hypoK is abd. Distention and small large bowel obstraction",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let low K make your gut go slow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of postoperative abdominal distention and small/large bowel obstruction without fever or tenderness is classic for paralytic ileus. Hypokalemia is a well-known and common electrolyte disturbance that directly contributes to the development of postoperative ileus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPotassium plays a crucial role in maintaining the resting membrane potential of smooth muscle cells and nerve conduction. Hypokalemia hyperpolarizes these cells, making them less excitable and impairing their ability to contract effectively. This leads to decreased gastrointestinal motility, resulting in the characteristic symptoms of paralytic ileus, including abdominal distention and bowel obstruction. Therefore, checking potassium levels pre- and post-operatively is critical.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hypo Mg) (Incorrect): While hypomagnesemia can cause muscle weakness and contribute to electrolyte imbalances, it is not as direct or common a primary cause of paralytic ileus as hypokalemia. It can, however, exacerbate hypokalemia.\nOption B (Hypo CL) (Incorrect): Hypochloremia is often associated with metabolic alkalosis and can occur secondary to vomiting or nasogastric suction, but it does not directly cause paralytic ileus through impaired smooth muscle function in the same way hypokalemia does.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Electrolyte Imbalance | Common GI Manifestation | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hypokalemia | Paralytic Ileus, Constipation | Hyperpolarization of smooth muscle cells, impaired contractility |\n| Hypomagnesemia | Muscle weakness, Tremors, Arrhythmias (can exacerbate hypokalemia) | Affects neuromuscular excitability, enzyme function |\n| Hypochloremia | Metabolic Alkalosis, Volume depletion | Often secondary to vomiting/NG suction, renal losses |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always check potassium levels pre- and post-op to prevent ileus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAbdominal X-rays would show diffusely dilated loops of small and large bowel with air-fluid levels, consistent with ileus. CT scan would confirm bowel dilation without a clear mechanical transition point.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEnhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Guidelines (e.g., ERAS Society Guidelines 2021): These guidelines emphasize meticulous fluid and electrolyte management, including potassium, to prevent postoperative ileus and promote early recovery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypo Mg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypo CL | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypo k | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) كلهم صح لكن اكثر شيء يطون سبب في Ileus شلل الامعاء = low k Key word : you shod check K before and af** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
