  "question": "417-Patient lost sensation over medial side of leg but motor function is intact. Which nerve is injured?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Obturator",
    "B": "Femora",
    "C": "Saphenous",
    "D": "Sciatic"
  },
  "answer": "C) lost sensation over = Mid thigh = obturator lost sensation over = medial side of leg = saphenous",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Saphenous nerve: purely sensory, purely medial leg.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Saphenous. The saphenous nerve is a purely sensory branch of the femoral nerve, responsible for providing sensation to the skin on the medial side of the leg and foot. Its isolated injury perfectly explains the patient's symptoms of lost sensation in this specific area without any motor deficits.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe saphenous nerve is the longest cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve. It emerges from the adductor canal, pierces the fascia lata, and descends superficially along the medial aspect of the leg, accompanying the great saphenous vein. Because it contains no motor fibers, damage to the saphenous nerve results in a distinct sensory deficit over the medial leg and ankle without affecting muscle function. This anatomical specificity is key to differentiating it from other major nerves in the lower limb.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Obturator) (Incorrect): The obturator nerve primarily supplies motor function to the adductor muscles of the thigh and provides sensation to a small area on the medial thigh, not the medial leg. Injury would cause adductor weakness.\nOption B (Femoral) (Incorrect): The femoral nerve is a major mixed nerve supplying motor function to the quadriceps femoris and sartorius muscles, and sensation to the anterior thigh and medial leg (via its saphenous branch). A femoral nerve injury would result in significant motor weakness (e.g., inability to extend the knee) in addition to sensory loss.\nOption D (Sciatic) (Incorrect): The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the body, providing motor and sensory innervation to the posterior thigh and nearly the entire leg and foot (except the medial leg). Injury to the sciatic nerve would cause widespread motor deficits (e.g., foot drop, hamstring weakness) and sensory loss over a much larger area.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution | Motor Function |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Saphenous | Femoral nerve | Medial leg & foot | None |\n| Obturator | Lumbar plexus (L2-L4) | Medial thigh | Adductor muscles |\n| Femoral | Lumbar plexus (L2-L4) | Anterior thigh, medial leg (via saphenous) | Quadriceps femoris, sartorius, pectineus |\n| Sciatic | Sacral plexus (L4-S3) | Posterior thigh, entire leg & foot (except medial leg) | Hamstrings, all muscles below knee |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial leg sensation without motor loss points to saphenous nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, the saphenous nerve is often encountered during procedures involving the medial knee or saphenous vein, such as vein harvesting or medial arthrotomy. It typically runs anterior to the great saphenous vein in the distal thigh and leg, making it vulnerable to iatrogenic injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGray's Anatomy, 42nd Edition, emphasizes precise knowledge of peripheral nerve anatomy and distribution for accurate neurological diagnosis and surgical planning.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Obturator | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Femora | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Saphenous | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Sciatic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) lost sensation over = Mid thigh = obturator lost sensation over = medial side of leg = saphenous** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
