  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the esophagus ruptures, air finds its way to the neck!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Boerhaave's syndrome. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of sudden onset upper abdominal pain after vomiting, combined with the critical finding of supraclavicular subcutaneous emphysema, which signifies mediastinal air from esophageal rupture.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBoerhaave's syndrome involves a spontaneous transmural rupture of the esophagus, typically occurring in the left posterolateral wall of the distal esophagus. This catastrophic event is usually precipitated by a sudden, forceful increase in intraesophageal pressure against a closed glottis, such as during severe vomiting or retching. The rupture allows gastric contents and air to extravasate into the mediastinum, leading to mediastinitis and pneumomediastinum. The air can then track superiorly into the neck, manifesting as subcutaneous emphysema, a pathognomonic sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (esophagitis) (Incorrect): Esophagitis is inflammation of the esophagus, causing pain and dysphagia, but does not involve perforation or subcutaneous emphysema.\nOption B (acute gastritis) (Incorrect): Acute gastritis is inflammation of the stomach lining, causing epigastric pain and nausea, but does not lead to esophageal rupture or subcutaneous emphysema.\nOption C (perforated peptic ulcer) (Incorrect): A perforated peptic ulcer causes sudden severe abdominal pain and peritonitis, often with free air under the diaphragm, but typically does not present with supraclavicular subcutaneous emphysema unless there is an unusual and extensive dissection of air into the mediastinum and neck, which is not the primary presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology | Key Symptoms | Diagnostic Clue |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Boerhaave's Syndrome | Forceful vomiting/retching | Sudden severe chest/epigastric pain, dyspnea | Subcutaneous emphysema, Hamman's sign |\n| Mallory-Weiss Tear | Forceful vomiting/retching | Hematemesis, epigastric pain | Upper GI endoscopy shows mucosal tear |\n| Perforated Peptic Ulcer | NSAID use, H. pylori | Sudden severe epigastric pain, peritonitis | Free air under diaphragm on imaging |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vomiting + supraclavicular emphysema = Boerhaave's until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nChest X-ray may show pneumomediastinum, pleural effusion, or subcutaneous emphysema. CT scan of the chest and abdomen with oral contrast is diagnostic, revealing esophageal wall disruption, mediastinal air/fluid, and often the site of perforation. Intraoperatively, a tear in the distal esophagus with mediastinal contamination would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guidelines 2019: Management of esophageal perforations. Recommends early diagnosis and multidisciplinary management, often involving surgical repair or endoscopic stenting depending on the perforation size, location, and patient stability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | esophagitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | acute gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | perforated peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | boerhaav’s syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) (is spontaneous perforation of the esophagus ) Key word: subconscious emphysema** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
