  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Own the error, tell the patient, build trust.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because in cases of retained surgical items, immediate and transparent disclosure to the patient is an ethical and professional imperative. This fosters trust, respects patient autonomy, and is a crucial step in managing adverse events.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis scenario highlights the paramount importance of patient-centered care and ethical medical practice. Retained surgical items are \"never events\" and demand full transparency. The ethical principles of beneficence (acting in the patient's best interest), non-maleficence (avoiding harm), and respect for autonomy (informing the patient to allow informed decisions) mandate immediate disclosure. Open communication about medical errors, even severe ones, is critical for maintaining patient trust, facilitating appropriate follow-up care, and allowing for systemic improvements in patient safety.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Issue complaint against assistant) (Incorrect): While internal accountability is important, the immediate priority is the patient's well-being and right to know. Internal complaints are secondary to patient disclosure.\nOption B (Call your lawyer and report the incident) (Incorrect): Seeking legal counsel is often prudent in such situations, but it should not precede or replace direct, honest communication with the patient. The patient's right to information takes precedence over the physician's legal protection in the immediate aftermath.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Action | Rationale | Priority |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Patient Disclosure** | Ethical duty, builds trust, legal requirement for informed consent/adverse events | Immediate & Primary |\n| **Internal Reporting** | Quality improvement, accountability, systemic prevention | High (after patient disclosure) |\n| **Legal Consultation** | Protects practitioner, guides process, ensures compliance | High (concurrent with or immediately after disclosure planning) |\n| **Blaming Others** | Unprofessional, deflects responsibility, erodes trust | Never |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Transparency and apology are paramount after a surgical error.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a retained surgical gauze (gossypiboma) can appear as a foreign material, often with a characteristic whorled or mottled appearance, sometimes with gas bubbles or calcifications, and associated inflammatory changes, as described in the question. Intraoperatively, a re-exploration would reveal the actual gauze, confirming the diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for Safe Surgery (2009) and Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) Patient Safety Primers (2019) recommend open disclosure of adverse events, including retained surgical items, to patients. The American College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Disclosure of Adverse Events (2015) also emphasizes this.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Issue complaint against assistant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Call your lawyer and report the incident | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | apologize to the patient and tell her what happened | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
