  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bleeding ulcer? 72 hours of IV PPI, no debate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, IV PPI for 72 hours then conversion to oral, because sustained profound acid suppression is crucial in the initial management of high-risk bleeding peptic ulcers to prevent rebleeding and promote clot stability. This regimen is specifically recommended for ulcers with high-risk stigmata after successful endoscopic hemostasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPPIs work by irreversibly inhibiting the H+/K+-ATPase pump in gastric parietal cells, leading to profound and prolonged acid suppression. In the context of a bleeding duodenal ulcer, maintaining an intragastric pH above 6 is critical to stabilize the clot, prevent fibrinolysis, and allow for healing. IV administration ensures rapid and consistent acid suppression, which is particularly important in the acute phase of bleeding to reduce rebleeding rates and improve patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (oral ppi) (Incorrect): Oral PPIs have a delayed onset of action and may not achieve the sustained profound acid suppression required in acute upper GI bleeding, leading to a higher risk of rebleeding.\nOption B (iv ppi for 24 hours then convert to oral) (Incorrect): While IV PPI is appropriate, 24 hours is generally insufficient for high-risk bleeding ulcers. Guidelines recommend 72 hours of continuous IV PPI infusion to optimize clot stability and reduce rebleeding rates.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | PPI Regimen | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| High-risk bleeding ulcer (e.g., Forrest Ia, Ib, IIa) | IV PPI continuous infusion for 72 hours, then oral PPI | Sustained profound acid suppression to stabilize clot and prevent rebleeding |\n| Low-risk bleeding ulcer (e.g., Forrest IIc, III) | Oral PPI twice daily for 4-8 weeks | Less aggressive initial acid suppression needed, focus on healing |\n| Non-bleeding ulcer (H. pylori negative) | Oral PPI once daily for 4-8 weeks | Promote healing and symptom relief |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High-risk bleeding ulcers need 72 hours of IV PPI for clot stability.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a 1cm duodenal ulcer with active bleeding (e.g., spurting, oozing) or a non-bleeding visible vessel (Forrest Ia, Ib, IIa), which are considered high-risk stigmata requiring aggressive management.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021) recommends IV PPI for 72 hours after successful endoscopic hemostasis for high-risk stigmata.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | oral ppi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | iv ppi for 24 hours then convert to oral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | iv ppi for 72 hours then convert to oral | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
