  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patch it up, then shut the acid down for 48!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, IV PPI for 48 hours followed by oral PPI. This approach ensures robust and consistent acid suppression in the critical immediate postoperative period following a Graham patch repair for a perforated duodenal ulcer, promoting healing and preventing recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Graham patch is a temporary repair for a perforated duodenal ulcer. The underlying pathology is often H. pylori infection or NSAID use, leading to excessive acid production or compromised mucosal defense. Aggressive acid suppression is paramount post-repair to reduce gastric acid secretion, facilitate ulcer healing, and prevent breakdown of the repair or re-perforation. IV PPIs provide rapid and complete inhibition of the H+/K+-ATPase pump, ensuring consistent acid control when oral intake is restricted or absorption is variable. A 48-hour IV course provides a sufficient initial period of maximal acid suppression before transitioning to long-term oral therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'High dose PPI' is too vague and does not specify route or duration, which are critical for effective post-operative management. \nOption B (Incorrect): IV PPI for 24 hours may be insufficient for optimal initial acid suppression in the context of a perforated ulcer, where robust and sustained acid control is crucial for healing and preventing complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Initial PPI Regimen | Duration of IV PPI | Total PPI Duration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Uncomplicated Duodenal Ulcer | Oral PPI | N/A | 4-8 weeks |\n| Bleeding Peptic Ulcer (post-endoscopy) | IV PPI bolus + infusion | 72 hours | Oral PPI for 4-8 weeks |\n| Perforated Duodenal Ulcer (post-repair) | IV PPI | 48 hours | Oral PPI for 4-8 weeks (or longer if H. pylori positive) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perforated ulcer repair needs 48 hours of IV PPI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a Graham patch involves suturing a pedicle of omentum over the perforated duodenal ulcer. On imaging (e.g., CT scan), a perforated ulcer would typically show free air under the diaphragm and localized fluid collections, which should resolve post-operatively.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile specific guidelines may vary, the general consensus from surgical societies like SAGES and ACS emphasizes robust acid suppression post-perforation repair, with IV PPIs being standard initially.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | High dose PPI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | IV ppi for 24 hours followed by oral PPI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | IV ppi for 48 hours followed by oral PPI | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
