  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Jaundiced sludge means the gallbladder must go.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cholecystectomy. This patient presents with symptomatic biliary sludge (jaundice) following sleeve gastrectomy, a condition known to increase the risk of gallstone formation. Definitive treatment is required to prevent further complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary sludge, also known as microlithiasis, can cause symptoms similar to gallstones, including biliary colic, pancreatitis, and jaundice. Jaundice indicates obstruction of the common bile duct, likely due to sludge migrating from the gallbladder. Patients undergoing rapid weight loss, such as after bariatric surgery, are at a significantly higher risk of developing gallstones and sludge. Cholecystectomy removes the source of the sludge (the gallbladder), thereby preventing recurrent symptoms and potential severe complications like cholangitis or pancreatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Expectant): Incorrect. Jaundice signifies symptomatic biliary obstruction, which necessitates intervention, not observation. Expectant management is reserved for asymptomatic biliary sludge.\nOption B (Endoscopic sphincterotomy): Incorrect. While endoscopic sphincterotomy can relieve common bile duct obstruction, it does not address the underlying problem of sludge formation in the gallbladder. It might be considered for retained CBD stones/sludge after cholecystectomy or in patients unfit for surgery, but cholecystectomy is the primary treatment for symptomatic gallbladder disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Symptoms | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Asymptomatic Biliary Sludge | None | Expectant management |\n| Symptomatic Biliary Sludge | Biliary colic, jaundice, pancreatitis | Cholecystectomy |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Biliary colic, jaundice, cholangitis, pancreatitis | ERCP + Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic biliary sludge, especially post-bariatric surgery, warrants cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, biliary sludge appears as low-amplitude echoes layering in the dependent portion of the gallbladder, without acoustic shadowing, and typically shifts with changes in patient position. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear normal or show signs of chronic inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines on Gallstone Disease (e.g., 2016). These guidelines recommend managing symptomatic gallstone disease (including sludge) with cholecystectomy, and consider prophylactic cholecystectomy for patients with pre-existing gallstones undergoing bariatric surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Expectant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Endoscopic sphincterotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
