  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't turn an elective chole into an unplanned gastrectomy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is to proceed with the cholecystectomy only. Finding a large stomach mass during an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy is an incidental finding that requires further workup, not immediate resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe principle here is that an elective, benign procedure should not be converted into a major, unplanned oncologic resection without proper preoperative staging, patient counseling, and consent. The cholecystectomy addresses the patient's primary complaint (e.g., symptomatic cholelithiasis), and the stomach mass, while concerning, is not an acute emergency preventing the completion of the planned surgery. Resecting a potentially malignant mass without a biopsy, staging scans, and a multidisciplinary discussion is not standard of care and could lead to suboptimal oncologic outcomes or unnecessary morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (stop oper) (Incorrect): Stopping the operation entirely would leave the patient with their original gallbladder pathology untreated and still require a separate procedure for the stomach mass. The cholecystectomy can safely be completed.\nOption C (chlesrecomy and resection mass) (Incorrect): Resecting a large stomach mass, especially one discovered incidentally, is a major undertaking. It requires extensive preoperative evaluation (biopsy, staging imaging like CT/PET), patient consent, and often a different surgical approach or team. Performing an unplanned gastrectomy or partial gastrectomy during an elective cholecystectomy is inappropriate and potentially harmful, as it bypasses critical steps in oncologic management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Incidental Finding Type | Recommended Action | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Benign, non-interfering (e.g., small adhesion) | Proceed with primary surgery | No impact on primary goal, no further workup needed |\n| Potentially malignant, non-acute (e.g., stomach mass) | Complete primary surgery, then stage and plan secondary procedure | Avoids unplanned major surgery; allows for proper workup and patient consent |\n| Acute, life-threatening (e.g., perforated viscus, major bleeding) | Address immediately | Patient safety dictates urgent intervention |\n| Benign, interfering (e.g., large adhesion preventing access) | Address as needed to complete primary surgery, or abort if too complex | Prioritize patient safety and completion of primary goal |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Incidental findings require careful consideration; don't escalate elective surgery without proper workup.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a large stomach mass might appear as a firm, exophytic, or infiltrative lesion on the gastric wall. It could be palpated or visualized through the laparoscope. Post-operatively, further imaging such as a CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis, followed by upper endoscopy with biopsy, would be crucial for diagnosis and staging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Incidental Findings (General Surgical Principles): Recommends a systematic approach to incidental findings, emphasizing patient safety, appropriate workup, and avoiding unnecessary or unplanned major procedures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | stop oper | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | cholecystectomy only | ✅ Correct |\n| C | chlesrecomy and resection mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
