  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Normal thyroid cells in a neck LN? Think ectopic, not malignancy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Ectopic. If a fine needle aspiration (FNA) of a neck lymph node reveals normal thyroid cells, the most likely diagnosis is ectopic thyroid tissue. This indicates the presence of benign thyroid tissue in an abnormal location, rather than metastatic cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEctopic thyroid tissue refers to thyroid follicular cells found outside the normal anatomical position of the thyroid gland. This can occur in various locations in the neck, such as within lymph nodes (struma lymphomatosa), along the thyroglossal duct tract, or as a lingual thyroid. The key differentiator here is the finding of *normal* thyroid cells. Metastatic thyroid cancer, whether papillary or follicular, would typically show malignant cytological features in the FNA, not benign, normal-appearing thyroid cells. Therefore, the presence of normal thyroid cells in a lymph node FNA points towards a benign developmental anomaly.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Follicular carcinoma metastasis to a lymph node would show malignant follicular cells, often with architectural atypia, not normal thyroid cells. \nOption C (Incorrect): Papillary carcinoma metastasis to a lymph node would show malignant papillary cells, characterized by specific nuclear features like Orphan Annie eye nuclei, nuclear grooves, and intranuclear inclusions, not normal thyroid cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Normal Thyroid Gland | Ectopic Thyroid Tissue (in LN) | Metastatic Thyroid Cancer (in LN) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Anterior neck, infra-hyoid | Anywhere in neck, often LN or thyroglossal tract | Lymph nodes, distant sites |\n| FNA Findings | Normal follicular cells | Normal follicular cells | Malignant cells (papillary, follicular, medullary, anaplastic features) |\n| Clinical Significance | Endocrine function | Benign, but can rarely undergo malignant transformation | Malignant, requires treatment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal thyroid cells in a LN FNA = ectopic thyroid, not cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, ectopic thyroid tissue in a lymph node might appear as a well-defined, often hyperechoic lesion within the node, mimicking normal thyroid parenchyma. Intraoperatively, it would appear as normal-looking thyroid tissue in an unexpected location.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015/2023). These guidelines discuss the evaluation of neck masses and the interpretation of FNA results, including the rare finding of ectopic thyroid tissue.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follicular ca | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Papillary ca | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ectopic | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
