  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't forget the venous side in arterial patients; DVT-PE is a silent killer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pulmonary Embolism (PE). Patients with peripheral vascular disease, especially those undergoing interventions like thrombolysis and experiencing prolonged hospitalization, are at significant risk for venous thromboembolism (VTE), which includes deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and subsequent PE.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatients with claudication often have underlying systemic atherosclerosis and may experience prolonged immobility during their hospital stay, both of which are major risk factors for developing a deep vein thrombosis (DVT). While thrombolysis targets existing arterial clots, it does not prevent new venous clot formation. If a DVT forms in the lower extremities and dislodges, it can travel through the right side of the heart and lodge in the pulmonary arteries, causing a life-threatening pulmonary embolism. The explicit mention of 'DVT case lead to p.E' in the key directly highlights this critical pathophysiological pathway.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Stroke) (Incorrect): While patients with vascular disease are at risk for stroke, particularly after arterial interventions or with underlying atrial fibrillation, the prompt's key explicitly points towards a DVT-related complication, which is a venous event, not typically a stroke.\nOption C (MI) (Incorrect): Myocardial infarction is a significant risk in patients with generalized atherosclerosis. However, it is an arterial event, and the provided key specifically links the risk to a DVT, which leads to a pulmonary embolism, a venous thromboembolic event, not an MI.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Pathophysiology | Risk Factors in Hospitalized Vascular Patients |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pulmonary Embolism (PE)** | Embolization of DVT from lower extremities to pulmonary arteries | Immobility, endothelial injury, hypercoagulability, vascular disease, surgery |\n| Stroke | Cerebral ischemia due to arterial thrombus/embolus or hemorrhage | Atherosclerosis, atrial fibrillation, carotid disease, hypertension, thrombolysis-related hemorrhage |\n| Myocardial Infarction (MI) | Coronary artery occlusion due to plaque rupture and thrombosis | Atherosclerosis, hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, stress of hospitalization |\n| Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) | Clot formation in deep veins, usually lower extremities | Immobility, surgery, trauma, malignancy, hypercoagulable states, vascular disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hospitalized vascular patients are high risk for DVT and subsequent PE.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor suspected PE, a CT Pulmonary Angiogram (CTPA) is the gold standard, showing filling defects in the pulmonary arteries. For DVT, duplex ultrasound of the lower extremities reveals non-compressible veins with absent flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACCP (American College of Chest Physicians) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy and Prevention of Thrombosis (9th Edition, 2012) recommend VTE prophylaxis for hospitalized medical and surgical patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Stroke | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | PE | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Key word : DVT case lead to p.E** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
