  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Image first, biopsy later, especially for liver masses.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is triphasic CT because it is the gold standard initial imaging modality for characterizing a newly discovered liver mass. In a patient with splenomegaly, there is often underlying liver disease (e.g., cirrhosis, portal hypertension), which increases the suspicion for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), making detailed vascular assessment crucial.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTriphasic CT involves imaging the liver during arterial, portal venous, and delayed phases. This multi-phase acquisition allows for detailed assessment of lesion vascularity, which is critical for differentiating benign from malignant lesions. For instance, hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) typically demonstrates arterial phase hyperenhancement followed by \"washout\" in the portal venous or delayed phases, a characteristic finding that can often be diagnostic without biopsy, particularly in cirrhotic patients. This detailed vascular information helps guide further management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): AFP (alpha-fetoprotein) is a tumor marker, not a primary diagnostic imaging study. While elevated AFP can support a diagnosis of HCC, it is neither sensitive nor specific enough to be used as a primary diagnostic tool for a liver mass and should always be used in conjunction with imaging.\nOption C (Incorrect): Biopsy is generally not the first step for a liver mass, especially if HCC is suspected, due to the risk of tumor seeding along the biopsy tract and potential for hemorrhage. Furthermore, characteristic imaging findings on triphasic CT or MRI can often be diagnostic for HCC, obviating the need for biopsy in many cases, particularly in patients with cirrhosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Tool | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Triphasic CT/MRI | Characterize liver masses, stage disease | High spatial resolution, detailed vascularity, often diagnostic for HCC | Radiation (CT), contrast risks, cost |\n| AFP | Tumor marker for HCC | Non-invasive blood test, useful for surveillance and prognosis | Low sensitivity/specificity, not diagnostic alone |\n| Biopsy | Histological confirmation | Definitive diagnosis, differentiate ambiguous lesions | Invasive, risk of bleeding/seeding, sampling error |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Triphasic CT is the initial imaging for liver mass characterization.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a triphasic CT, a typical hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) would appear as an arterial phase hyperenhancing lesion that demonstrates \"washout\" (hypoenhancement relative to surrounding liver parenchyma) in the portal venous and/or delayed phases. The splenomegaly would be visible, suggesting underlying portal hypertension or chronic liver disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2018 Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends multiphasic CT or MRI for diagnosis of HCC in patients at risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | AFP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | triphasic CT | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Key word: liver mass diagnosis with triphasic CT** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
