  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meigs: Benign tumor, fluid, resection, histology is key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Tissue histopathology. Meigs syndrome is a clinical triad involving a benign ovarian tumor, ascites, and pleural effusion. Definitive diagnosis hinges on confirming the benign nature of the ovarian mass through microscopic examination of the resected tissue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeigs syndrome is characterized by a benign ovarian tumor (most commonly a fibroma, but also thecoma or granulosa cell tumor) accompanied by ascites and a pleural effusion, which classically resolve after tumor resection. The critical aspect of the diagnosis is proving the benignity of the ovarian mass. Histopathological examination allows for precise classification of the tumor type and, crucially, excludes malignancy, which would classify the condition as Pseudo-Meigs syndrome. This confirmation is paramount for appropriate patient management and prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Tumor markers, such as CA-125, can be elevated in Meigs syndrome due to peritoneal irritation from ascites, but they are neither specific nor diagnostic. They cannot definitively confirm the benign nature of the tumor or rule out malignancy, which is essential for the diagnosis of Meigs syndrome.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Meigs Syndrome | Pseudo-Meigs Syndrome | Ovarian Malignancy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ovarian Tumor | Benign (fibroma, thecoma) | Malignant or inflammatory pelvic tumor | Malignant (epithelial, germ cell, stromal) |\n| Ascites & Pleural Effusion | Present | Present | Often present |\n| Resolution Post-Resection | Yes, complete | Yes, complete | No, often progresses |\n| Definitive Diagnosis | Tissue Histopathology | Tissue Histopathology | Tissue Histopathology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meigs syndrome: Histology confirms benign ovarian tumor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound, CT) would typically reveal a solid or complex ovarian mass, ascites, and a pleural effusion. Intraoperatively, a benign-appearing ovarian tumor would be identified, often a fibroma, which is then resected.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no specific guideline solely addresses Meigs syndrome diagnosis, the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) and Society of Gynecologic Oncology (SGO) guidelines for evaluation of adnexal masses (e.g., ACOG Practice Bulletin No. 205, 2019) emphasize histopathological diagnosis for definitive characterization of any ovarian tumor.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tissue histopathology | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Tumor marker | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Keyword: meigs syndrome is triad of benign (ovarian tumor +ascites + PE) Resolved after resection of** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
