  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Big HCC needs TACE, small HCC gets the knife.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Transcatheter Arterial Chemoembolization (TACE). For a 6 cm hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) lesion, especially in the context of Hepatitis B, TACE is the appropriate locoregional therapy when surgical resection is often not the primary choice due to lesion size.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTACE is a highly effective locoregional treatment for intermediate-stage HCC. It works by selectively delivering a high dose of chemotherapy directly to the tumor via its arterial blood supply, followed by embolization of the feeding arteries. This dual mechanism leads to tumor ischemia and necrosis, exploiting the fact that HCC typically derives its blood supply predominantly from the hepatic artery, while healthy liver parenchyma is supplied by the portal vein. This allows for targeted therapy with minimal systemic side effects.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Excision): Incorrect. Surgical resection (excision) is the preferred curative treatment for small, solitary HCC lesions (typically <5 cm) in patients with preserved liver function. A 6 cm lesion often falls outside the optimal criteria for primary resection, especially if there are underlying liver comorbidities like Hepatitis B-related cirrhosis.\nOption C (systemic chemo therapy): Incorrect. Systemic chemotherapy is generally reserved for advanced or metastatic HCC, or when locoregional therapies are not feasible. For a localized 6 cm lesion, TACE offers superior tumor control and survival benefits with a more favorable side effect profile compared to systemic chemotherapy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion Size/Stage | Treatment Option | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Very Early (<2 cm, solitary) | RFA (Radiofrequency Ablation) / PEI (Percutaneous Ethanol Injection) | Minimally invasive, curative for small lesions |\n| Early (<5 cm, solitary) | Surgical Resection (Excision) / Liver Transplant | Curative intent, good prognosis, transplant for severe cirrhosis |\n| Intermediate (>5 cm or multifocal) | TACE (Transcatheter Arterial Chemoembolization) | Locoregional control, exploits arterial supply of HCC |\n| Advanced (Vascular invasion/Metastasis) | Systemic Therapy (e.g., Sorafenib, Lenvatinib) | Palliative, extends survival, improves quality of life |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HCC >5cm, think TACE; <5cm, think resection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), a 6 cm HCC lesion would typically demonstrate arterial phase hyperenhancement with subsequent portal venous/delayed phase washout, often with a capsule. Pre-TACE angiography would confirm the hypervascular nature of the tumor and delineate its feeding arteries for targeted embolization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma (2023) recommends TACE for intermediate-stage HCC (BCLC B) that is not amenable to resection or ablation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | TACE Transcatheter arterial chemoembolization) more than 5 حقن الكبد | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | systemic chemo therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Keyword: less than 5 cm do excision , more than cm do TAC** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
