  "answer": "D) Keyword: or gall bladder stone in another Q Cholecystokinin cause relaxation and stamulation of gall bladder, intestine ,biliary colic This hormones for All GIT The most common cause of gall bladder stone is biliary colic",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CCK makes your gallbladder squeeze, causing colic with ease!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, cholecystokinin. Biliary colic is characterized by episodic right upper quadrant pain, typically triggered by fatty meals. This pain arises from the temporary obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone, exacerbated by gallbladder contraction stimulated by cholecystokinin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is a hormone released from the duodenum in response to the presence of fats and proteins. Its primary physiological role in the biliary system is to stimulate the contraction of the gallbladder and relax the sphincter of Oddi, thereby facilitating the release of bile into the small intestine for digestion. In the context of cholelithiasis, when a gallstone temporarily obstructs the cystic duct, the CCK-induced contraction of the gallbladder against this obstruction leads to increased intraluminal pressure and the characteristic spasmodic pain known as biliary colic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bilirubin) (Incorrect): Elevated bilirubin, particularly conjugated bilirubin, is typically associated with obstruction of the common bile duct (choledocholithiasis) or liver dysfunction, not directly with uncomplicated biliary colic.\nOption B (Amylase) (Incorrect): Amylase is an enzyme primarily indicative of pancreatic inflammation (pancreatitis). While gallstones can cause pancreatitis, amylase elevation is not a direct feature of isolated biliary colic.\nOption C (Alkaline phosphatase.) (Incorrect): Elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is a marker of cholestasis, often seen with common bile duct obstruction or other liver diseases, similar to bilirubin, and is not directly associated with uncomplicated biliary colic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Cause | Key Symptoms | Lab Findings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Biliary Colic | Gallstone temporarily obstructing cystic duct | Episodic RUQ pain, post-prandial, resolves within hours | Typically normal LFTs, amylase, lipase |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | Prolonged cystic duct obstruction, inflammation | Persistent RUQ pain (>6 hrs), fever, leukocytosis, Murphy's sign | Leukocytosis, mild LFT elevation possible |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Gallstone in common bile duct | RUQ pain, jaundice, dark urine, pale stools, cholangitis | Elevated conjugated bilirubin, ALP, GGT |\n| Gallstone Pancreatitis | Gallstone obstructing pancreatic duct/ampulla | Severe epigastric pain radiating to back, nausea, vomiting | Elevated amylase, lipase |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biliary colic = CCK-induced gallbladder contraction against a cystic duct stone.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the primary imaging modality, gallstones would be visible within the gallbladder lumen, often with acoustic shadowing. During an episode of biliary colic, the gallbladder may appear contracted around the stones. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder typically appears normal or mildly inflamed, containing stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommends cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis (biliary colic) to prevent recurrent episodes and complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bilirubin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amylase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Alkaline phosphatase. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cholecystokinin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Keyword: or gall bladder stone in another Q Cholecystokinin cause relaxation and stamulation of gall** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
