  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Coffee bean on X-ray? Think twisted sigmoid, not just a morning brew!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Sigmoid. The clinical presentation of constipation and distention in an elderly patient, combined with the pathognomonic \"coffee bean appearance\" on the abdominal X-ray, is classic for sigmoid volvulus, indicating an obstruction at the sigmoid colon.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid volvulus is a closed-loop obstruction caused by the twisting of the sigmoid colon around its mesentery. This twisting leads to luminal obstruction and can compromise the blood supply, potentially causing ischemia and perforation. The characteristic \"coffee bean sign\" seen on plain abdominal X-ray is formed by the massively dilated, gas-filled sigmoid loop, with the central linear density representing the apposed walls of the twisted bowel. This distinct radiographic finding is crucial for rapid diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ceccal) (Incorrect): Cecal volvulus is a less common form of colonic volvulus. While it also causes obstruction, its radiographic appearance is typically a kidney-bean shape or a single large air-filled viscus, often located in the right upper quadrant, and does not present with the classic \"coffee bean\" sign.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sigmoid Volvulus | Cecal Volvulus |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | Most common (70-80% of colonic volvulus) | Less common (15-20%) |\n| X-ray Sign | \"Coffee bean\" sign, inverted U-shape, often in LLQ/mid-abdomen | \"Kidney bean\" sign, single dilated loop, often in RUQ |\n| Risk Factors | Chronic constipation, high fiber diet, institutionalized patients | Mobile cecum, incomplete fixation |\n| Treatment | Endoscopic detorsion (initial), then elective resection; emergent resection if ischemia | Right hemicolectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The \"coffee bean sign\" on X-ray is diagnostic for sigmoid volvulus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe provided image, an abdominal X-ray, clearly demonstrates the classic \"coffee bean sign,\" which is pathognomonic for sigmoid volvulus. This sign represents a massively dilated, gas-filled loop of sigmoid colon, often extending from the pelvis into the upper abdomen, with a central linear density representing the apposed walls of the twisted loop.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016): Recommends initial endoscopic detorsion for sigmoid volvulus in stable patients, followed by elective resection to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ceccal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sigmoid | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Keyword: coffee signs** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
