  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Respecting patient preference builds trust and ensures care.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is to respect the patient's request for a female doctor. This approach upholds patient autonomy and fosters trust, which is crucial for effective healthcare delivery, especially during sensitive examinations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRespecting a patient's preference, particularly regarding the gender of an examiner for a sensitive procedure like a breast examination, is a fundamental aspect of patient-centered care and medical ethics. It acknowledges the patient's right to bodily autonomy and comfort, which can significantly impact their willingness to undergo necessary examinations and adhere to medical advice. Accommodating such requests, when logistically possible, demonstrates empathy and professionalism, strengthening the patient-provider relationship.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Refusing the patient's request without exploring alternatives or understanding the underlying reasons is dismissive of patient autonomy and can lead to a breakdown in trust. It may also deter the patient from seeking necessary medical care.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ethical Principle | Definition | Application in this scenario |\n| :---------------- | :--------- | :-------------------------- |\n| Autonomy | Respecting a patient's right to make decisions about their own medical care. | Accommodating the patient's preference for a female examiner. |\n| Beneficence | Acting in the best interest of the patient. | Ensuring the patient feels comfortable enough to proceed with a vital examination. |\n| Non-maleficence | Do no harm. | Avoiding actions that could cause psychological distress or deter necessary care. |\n| Justice | Fair and equitable distribution of healthcare resources and treatment. | Ensuring all patients receive respectful and appropriate care, regardless of personal preferences. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Patient autonomy and comfort are paramount in sensitive examinations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to ethical communication and patient-centered care, not imaging or intraoperative findings. Therefore, there are no relevant imaging or intraoperative pearls.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Medical Association (AMA) Code of Medical Ethics (2016). It emphasizes patient autonomy and the physician's responsibility to respect patient preferences and ensure comfort, especially in sensitive situations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | refuse | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | respect | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
