  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Size matters for excision, margins are key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, wide local excision. This is because phyllodes tumors less than 10 cm, especially benign or borderline ones, are typically managed with wide local excision to achieve clear margins while preserving breast tissue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors are fibroepithelial tumors of the breast with a propensity for local recurrence if not adequately excised. Wide local excision aims to remove the tumor with a 1 cm or greater margin of healthy tissue to minimize recurrence risk. This approach balances oncologic control with cosmetic outcomes for smaller tumors, making it the preferred treatment for a 4-5 cm lesion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is an overtreatment for a 4-5 cm phyllodes tumor, especially if benign or borderline. It is reserved for very large tumors (typically >10 cm), recurrent tumors, or those with malignant features where clear margins cannot be achieved with less extensive surgery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type/Size | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Benign/Borderline Phyllodes Tumor < 10 cm | Wide Local Excision | Achieve clear margins (1 cm) to prevent local recurrence while preserving breast tissue. |\n| Benign/Borderline Phyllodes Tumor > 10 cm or recurrent | Simple Mastectomy | Larger tumors or recurrences may require more extensive resection to achieve clear margins. |\n| Malignant Phyllodes Tumor | Simple Mastectomy | Due to higher risk of local recurrence and potential for distant metastasis, though axillary staging is generally not indicated unless clinically suspicious. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phyllodes <10cm = wide local excision; >10cm or malignant = simple mastectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound/mammogram) typically shows a well-circumscribed, lobulated mass, often with cystic areas. Intraoperatively, phyllodes tumors are usually firm, well-demarcated, and may have a leaf-like or whorled appearance on cut section.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer, 2023. These guidelines recommend wide local excision with clear margins (at least 1 cm) for benign and borderline phyllodes tumors, and simple mastectomy for malignant or very large/recurrent tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | wide local excision | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) phylloid less than 10cm benign = wide locl excision Above 10 cm simple mastectomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
