  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lungs are the Achilles' heel of malignant phyllodes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Contrast CT of chest. Malignant phyllodes tumors, while rare, have a distinct metastatic pattern primarily involving hematogenous spread to the lungs, making a chest CT the essential next step for staging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are fibroepithelial neoplasms of the breast with a propensity for distant metastasis in 10-20% of cases. Unlike invasive ductal carcinoma, lymphatic spread is uncommon; instead, these tumors predominantly metastasize via the bloodstream to the lungs, followed by bone and liver. A contrast-enhanced CT of the chest is the most sensitive and appropriate imaging modality to detect pulmonary metastases, which are the most common site of distant disease and critical for guiding prognosis and treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (pet scan) (Incorrect): PET scans are generally not recommended for routine staging of malignant phyllodes tumors. Their utility is limited due to variable uptake and they do not offer a significant advantage over conventional imaging like CT chest for detecting the primary metastatic sites (lungs). PET scans may be considered in cases of suspected widespread metastatic disease or for evaluating equivocal findings, but not as the initial staging step.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Malignant Phyllodes Tumor | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Metastatic Route | Hematogenous | Lymphatic, then hematogenous |\n| Most Common Distant Site | Lungs | Bone, lung, liver, brain |\n| Initial Staging for Metastasis | CT chest | CT chest/abdomen/pelvis, bone scan (for advanced stages) |\n| Role of Lymph Node Dissection | Rarely indicated | Often indicated for positive nodes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes? Think lungs first; CT chest is your best bet.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest CT, pulmonary metastases from malignant phyllodes tumors typically appear as well-defined, often multiple, nodules of varying sizes in the lung parenchyma. These can range from small, subcentimeter lesions to larger masses.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023) recommend imaging for distant metastasis, typically with CT chest, for malignant phyllodes tumors due to their metastatic potential.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Contrast ct of chest | ✅ Correct |\n| B | pet scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
