  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Malignant phyllodes: Check the lungs before you cut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Chest CT without contrast. This is because malignant phyllodes tumors have a distinct metastatic pattern, primarily spreading hematogenously to distant sites, most commonly the lungs, rather than via lymphatics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are rare fibroepithelial tumors of the breast. Unlike invasive ductal carcinoma, they rarely metastasize to regional lymph nodes. Instead, their primary route of distant spread is hematogenous, with the lungs being the most frequent site of metastasis. Therefore, after a biopsy confirms malignancy, the next appropriate step is to stage for distant disease, and a Chest CT is the most sensitive and specific initial imaging modality to detect pulmonary metastases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (WLE - Wide Local Excision) (Incorrect): While WLE is the definitive local treatment for malignant phyllodes, staging for distant metastatic disease is crucial and typically performed before definitive surgery for the primary tumor, especially given the high metastatic potential to the lungs.\nOption B (PET scan) (Incorrect): A PET scan can detect metastases, but it is not typically the first-line or most appropriate initial staging modality for malignant phyllodes tumors. Chest CT is generally preferred for initial evaluation of pulmonary metastases, which are the most common, due to its higher resolution for lung parenchyma and cost-effectiveness. PET scans may be considered if CT findings are equivocal or for systemic staging in other contexts.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes | Borderline Phyllodes | Malignant Phyllodes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Metastatic Potential | Rare | Low | High (hematogenous) |\n| Local Recurrence | Low | Moderate | High |\n| Treatment | WLE with 1cm margin | WLE with 1-2cm margin | WLE with >1-2cm margin + Staging for mets |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes: think lungs, not nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA Chest CT would be performed to identify any pulmonary nodules or masses, which would indicate metastatic disease from the malignant phyllodes tumor.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) or specific guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma often provide guidance on the staging and management of malignant phyllodes tumors, emphasizing the importance of distant metastatic workup.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | PET scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chest CT witout contrast | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Keyword: malignant** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
