  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstones first, CT later for pancreatitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct next step for a patient presenting with typical pancreatitis symptoms (epigastric pain, high amylase) is an abdominal ultrasound (US). This is because identifying the etiology, particularly gallstones, is crucial for initial management and preventing recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis is often caused by gallstones, which can obstruct the pancreatic duct. An abdominal ultrasound is the best initial imaging modality to evaluate for cholelithiasis and biliary obstruction, which are common and treatable causes of pancreatitis. It is non-invasive, readily available, and does not involve radiation, making it an excellent first-line investigation to guide further management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (CT scan) (Incorrect): While a CT scan is excellent for confirming the diagnosis, assessing the severity of pancreatitis, and identifying complications like necrosis or fluid collections, it is not the *initial* step. The priority is to identify the cause, especially gallstones, which US is superior for in the acute setting.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ultrasound (US) | CT Scan | Amylase | Lipase |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Role in Pancreatitis** | Best initial imaging to identify biliary etiology (gallstones) | Confirms diagnosis, assesses severity, identifies complications (necrosis, fluid collections) | Sensitive for pancreatitis, less specific | More specific for pancreatitis, stays elevated longer |\n| **Advantages** | Non-invasive, no radiation, cost-effective, good for biliary tree | Detailed imaging of pancreas and retroperitoneum | Readily available, quick result | More reliable than amylase, especially in alcoholic pancreatitis |\n| **Disadvantages** | Operator dependent, limited view of pancreas in obese patients/bowel gas | Radiation exposure, contrast risks, higher cost, not initial for etiology | Can be elevated in other conditions (e.g., salivary gland disease, bowel ischemia) | Can be elevated in other conditions (e.g., renal failure, celiac disease) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Initial pancreatitis imaging: US for stones, CT for complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would look for gallstones in the gallbladder, common bile duct dilation, or signs of choledocholithiasis. Pancreatic edema might also be visible. A CT scan, if performed later, would show diffuse or focal enlargement of the pancreas, peripancreatic fat stranding, and potentially fluid collections or necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013) recommends abdominal ultrasound as the initial imaging study in all patients with acute pancreatitis to identify gallstones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ✅ Correct |\n| B | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Keyword: in pancreatitis :best initial = Us Confirm= ct Amylase = sensitive Lipase = specific** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
