  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's thick-walled and 5 weeks, think necrosis, not just fluid.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Walled-off necrosis (WON). This diagnosis is supported by the patient's presentation 5 weeks post-pancreatitis, the large, thick-walled fluid collection on ultrasound, and systemic inflammatory response (elevated WBC), all consistent with the evolution of necrotizing pancreatitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWalled-off necrosis (WON) represents a mature collection of necrotic pancreatic and/or peripancreatic tissue, fluid, and debris, encapsulated by a well-defined inflammatory wall. It typically develops more than 4 weeks after an episode of acute necrotizing pancreatitis. The thick wall seen on ultrasound signifies this maturation process. The persistent symptoms like epigastric tenderness, vomiting, and inability to tolerate food are common with large, symptomatic WON, often due to mass effect or inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pseudocyst) (Incorrect): While a pseudocyst also forms >4 weeks and has a wall, it is primarily a collection of *pancreatic fluid* without significant necrotic tissue. The description of a \"mass\" with \"fluid inside\" after severe pancreatitis is more indicative of WON, which contains both fluid and solid necrotic debris.\nOption B (Abscess) (Incorrect): A pancreatic abscess is a localized collection of pus. While the elevated WBC suggests inflammation or potential infection, the primary description of a \"mass with thick wall and fluid inside\" is more characteristic of WON, which can *become* infected (infected WON) but is not primarily an abscess. An abscess would typically be described as a purulent collection, often with gas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Peripancreatic Fluid Collection (APFC) | Pancreatic Pseudocyst | Walled-off Necrosis (WON) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Time from Pancreatitis** | < 4 weeks | > 4 weeks | > 4 weeks |\n| **Contents** | Homogeneous fluid | Homogeneous fluid | Heterogeneous (fluid + necrotic debris) |\n| **Wall** | No well-defined wall | Well-defined wall | Well-defined wall |\n| **Location** | Peripancreatic | Intra- or peripancreatic | Intra- or peripancreatic |\n| **Associated Pancreatitis** | Interstitial edematous | Interstitial edematous | Necrotizing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The 4-week rule and contents (fluid vs. necrosis) differentiate pancreatic collections.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, WON appears as a complex, heterogeneous mass with both fluid and solid components, surrounded by a thick, irregular wall. CT scan would further characterize the solid necrotic debris within the collection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe revised Atlanta Classification of Acute Pancreatitis (2012) defines and differentiates these pancreatic fluid collections based on timing, content, and presence of a wall.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pseudocyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Walled off necrosis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
