  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's cystic, late, and not hot, think pseudocyst, not rot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. A pancreatic pseudocyst is the most likely diagnosis because the patient presents 6 weeks after an acute pancreatitis episode with a cystic collection on CT and no signs of infection (no fever), which aligns perfectly with the definition and typical presentation of a pancreatic pseudocyst.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic pseudocysts are encapsulated collections of pancreatic fluid, necrotic debris, and inflammatory exudates, typically forming 4-6 weeks after an episode of acute pancreatitis. They lack an epithelial lining, hence 'pseudo' cyst, and are walled off by granulation tissue and fibrosis. The persistent vomiting and epigastric fullness are due to mass effect from the growing collection, compressing adjacent structures like the stomach or duodenum, leading to the observed symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Pancreatic abscess) (Incorrect): Pancreatic abscesses are typically infected collections, and the absence of fever makes this diagnosis less likely. Abscesses often contain gas and are more heterogeneous than a simple pseudocyst.\nOption C (Pancreatic necrosis) (Incorrect): Pancreatic necrosis refers to non-viable pancreatic tissue, which would appear as non-enhancing areas on CT. While a pseudocyst can form from necrotic debris, the CT describes a 'cystic collection,' not solid or non-enhancing tissue, and the 6-week timeframe points to a more organized, fluid-filled collection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pancreatic Pseudocyst | Pancreatic Abscess | Walled-off Necrosis (WON) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Timing** | >4 weeks post-pancreatitis | Variable, often later with infection | >4 weeks post-pancreatitis |\n| **CT Appearance** | Well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection, homogeneous | Heterogeneous fluid collection, often with gas bubbles, ill-defined | Heterogeneous collection of fluid and solid necrotic debris, encapsulated |\n| **Symptoms** | Epigastric pain, fullness, vomiting, no fever | Fever, leukocytosis, severe abdominal pain, sepsis | Similar to pseudocyst, but often more severe symptoms if infected |\n| **Pathology** | Fluid collection without epithelial lining | Infected collection of fluid and necrotic tissue | Encapsulated collection of both fluid and solid necrotic tissue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A cystic collection >4 weeks post-pancreatitis without fever is a pseudocyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a pancreatic pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, usually unilocular, fluid-attenuation collection adjacent to or within the pancreas, often with a smooth, enhancing wall representing the fibrous capsule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Association of Pancreatology (IAP)/American Pancreatic Association (APA) Guidelines 2012 for the management of acute pancreatitis. These guidelines define pseudocysts as encapsulated collections of fluid with a well-defined wall, occurring typically >4 weeks after acute pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pseudo cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pancreatic abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pancreatic necrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
