  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just aspirate; let it flow internally!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The question presents a very large pancreatic pseudocyst (18 cm x 24 cm). For such a significant, presumably symptomatic and mature pseudocyst, active intervention is indicated, and endoscopic drainage is the preferred minimally invasive approach for non-infected cases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEndoscopic drainage involves creating an internal communication between the pseudocyst and the gastrointestinal tract, typically the stomach (cystogastrostomy) or duodenum (cystoduodenostomy), using an endoscope. This allows continuous internal drainage of the fluid, effectively relieving symptoms and preventing complications. This method is less invasive than surgical drainage and avoids the risks of external fistula and high recurrence associated with simple percutaneous aspiration, especially for large, mature pseudocysts that are not infected.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (per cutaneous aspiration): Incorrect. While percutaneous drainage can be used, particularly for infected pseudocysts or as a temporizing measure, simple aspiration has a very high recurrence rate for large pseudocysts. Long-term percutaneous catheter drainage carries risks of infection, catheter dislodgement, and external pancreatic fistula, and is generally reserved for infected collections or patients unsuitable for endoscopic/surgical drainage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | < 6 cm, < 6 weeks | > 6 cm or symptomatic, > 6 weeks, non-infected | Infected pseudocyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Management | Observation | Endoscopic drainage (cystogastrostomy/duodenostomy) | Percutaneous catheter drainage, followed by definitive drainage if needed |\n| Rationale | Often resolves spontaneously | Minimally invasive, effective internal drainage, lower morbidity than surgery | Controls infection, avoids spillage, can be definitive or bridge to surgery/endoscopy |\n| Complications | Rare | Bleeding, perforation, recurrence | Sepsis, fistula, catheter-related issues |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Large, non-infected pseudocyst? Endoscopic drainage is often the first choice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging like CT or MRI, a pancreatic pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection, typically adjacent to the pancreas. Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is crucial for guiding endoscopic drainage, identifying the closest GI lumen, and ensuring no intervening vessels. During endoscopic drainage, a cystogastrostomy or cystoduodenostomy is created, often with stent placement, allowing the pseudocyst contents to drain into the stomach or duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guideline on the Management of Pancreatic Necrosis (2018): Recommends endoscopic drainage for symptomatic, mature pancreatic pseudocysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | per cutaneous aspiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | endoscopic drainage | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Pancreatic pseudocyst ttt: - less than 6 cm and 6 week > observation - more than 6 cm and 6 week > d** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
