  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Alcohol + back pain = pancreas in distress!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis answer is correct. The classic presentation of an alcoholic patient with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back is highly suggestive of acute pancreatitis, a common and serious complication of chronic alcohol abuse.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis, particularly alcoholic pancreatitis, is characterized by autodigestion of the pancreas by prematurely activated digestive enzymes. Alcohol is thought to sensitize acinar cells to cholecystokinin, leading to premature enzyme activation and duct obstruction. The retroperitoneal location of the pancreas explains the characteristic radiation of pain to the back, often described as boring or knife-like, as the inflammation irritates surrounding retroperitoneal structures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Stomach cancer typically presents with chronic symptoms like weight loss, early satiety, dysphagia, or upper GI bleeding, not acute severe abdominal pain radiating to the back as its primary acute presentation. While it can cause pain, the radiation pattern and acute onset in an alcoholic patient are not typical for stomach cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Pancreatitis | Peptic Ulcer Disease (Perforated) | Biliary Colic/Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Character** | Severe, epigastric, radiating to back, boring | Sudden, severe, generalized abdominal, \"knife-like\" | RUQ, episodic, radiating to right shoulder/scapula |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Nausea, vomiting, fever, tachycardia, tenderness | Nausea, vomiting, guarding, rigidity, rebound | Nausea, vomiting, fever (cholecystitis), Murphy's sign |\n| **Risk Factors** | Alcohol, gallstones, hypertriglyceridemia | H. pylori, NSAIDs, stress | Gallstones, obesity, female, fertile, forty |\n| **Diagnosis** | Elevated amylase/lipase, CT abdomen | Upright CXR (free air), CT abdomen | Ultrasound (gallstones, wall thickening) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Alcoholic + severe epigastric pain radiating to back = think pancreatitis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT abdomen with IV contrast would typically show an enlarged, edematous pancreas, peripancreatic fat stranding, and potentially fluid collections or necrosis. In severe cases, ascites or pleural effusions may be present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). It recommends early diagnosis based on clinical presentation, elevated pancreatic enzymes, and characteristic imaging findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | stomach cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | alcoholic pancreatitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
