  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatitis: Don't just treat the pain, anticipate the drain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nUrgent surgical consultation is the correct next step in the management of pancreatitis. While initial resuscitation with IVF and pain control is crucial, pancreatitis can rapidly progress or present with complications requiring surgical intervention, making early surgical evaluation paramount.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis can lead to severe complications such as infected necrosis, pseudocyst formation, or biliary obstruction (especially in gallstone pancreatitis). An early surgical consultation allows for a comprehensive assessment of the patient's condition, including severity scoring (e.g., Ranson's, APACHE II), identification of the etiology (e.g., gallstones requiring ERCP or cholecystectomy), and proactive planning for potential interventions like drainage of fluid collections or debridement of necrotic tissue. This proactive approach ensures timely intervention if the patient's condition deteriorates or complications arise, optimizing patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ppi) (Incorrect): While PPIs may be used for stress ulcer prophylaxis in severe pancreatitis, they are not the immediate next critical step after initial resuscitation and do not address the potential for surgical complications or etiology.\nOption B (Antibiotics) (Incorrect): Prophylactic antibiotics are generally not recommended in acute pancreatitis unless there is documented evidence of infection (e.g., infected necrosis). Routine use can lead to antibiotic resistance and does not improve outcomes in sterile pancreatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Intervention | Indication | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| IVF & Pain Control | All acute pancreatitis | Resuscitation, symptom management, prevent organ failure |\n| Surgical Consultation | Severe pancreatitis, biliary etiology, complications (e.g., necrosis, pseudocyst) | Assess need for ERCP, cholecystectomy, drainage, or debridement |\n| Antibiotics | Documented infected necrosis | Treat infection, prevent sepsis |\n| PPI | Severe pancreatitis (stress ulcer prophylaxis) | Prevent GI bleeding from stress ulcers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always involve surgery early for pancreatitis; complications can be deadly.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT scan with IV contrast would be crucial to assess the severity of pancreatitis, identify necrosis, fluid collections, or pseudocysts, and rule out other intra-abdominal pathologies. In cases of gallstone pancreatitis, ultrasound would confirm cholelithiasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013). It recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration, pain control, and identification of etiology. Surgical consultation is indicated for specific complications or if a biliary etiology requires intervention (e.g., ERCP for choledocholithiasis).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ppi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urgent surgical consultation | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
