  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When extensors fail, think Radial; when flexors flail, consider Median.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Radial nerve. The patient's symptoms of difficulty with dorsiflexion and finger extension are classic signs of radial nerve dysfunction, as this nerve innervates the extensor muscles of the wrist and fingers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radial nerve, originating from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus, is responsible for innervating the triceps brachii, anconeus, and the extensors of the wrist and fingers (e.g., extensor carpi radialis longus/brevis, extensor digitorum). Its sensory distribution covers the posterior aspect of the arm and forearm, and the dorsal aspect of the hand, thumb, index, middle, and half of the ring finger. Damage to the radial nerve typically results in \"wrist drop\" and inability to extend the fingers, precisely matching the patient's motor deficits.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Median nerve primarily innervates the flexors of the forearm and hand, and the thenar muscles. Its sensory distribution is to the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, middle, and half of the ring finger. Median nerve injury would cause deficits in thumb opposition, flexion of the index and middle fingers, and sensory loss in its palmar distribution, not problems with dorsiflexion or finger extension.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Motor Function | Sensory Distribution | Classic Deficit |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radial | Wrist/finger extension, forearm supination | Dorsal arm/forearm, dorsal hand (thumb, index, middle, half ring) | Wrist drop, inability to extend fingers |\n| Median | Forearm pronation, wrist/finger flexion (radial side), thumb opposition | Palmar thumb, index, middle, half ring | Ape hand deformity, loss of thumb opposition, carpal tunnel syndrome |\n| Ulnar | Finger abduction/adduction, wrist flexion (ulnar side), intrinsic hand muscles | Palmar/dorsal half ring, little finger | Claw hand deformity, loss of finger adduction/abduction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wrist drop and finger extension loss scream Radial nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile no image is provided, in cases of suspected radial nerve injury, nerve conduction studies and electromyography (NCS/EMG) are crucial for localizing the lesion and assessing severity. Intraoperatively, the radial nerve is vulnerable in the spiral groove of the humerus, often seen with humeral shaft fractures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) 2014 Clinical Practice Guideline: The Diagnosis and Treatment of Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. While this guideline focuses on CTS (median nerve), it highlights the importance of differentiating nerve entrapments. For radial nerve, general peripheral nerve injury management principles apply.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Median | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radial | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
