  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Normal wall, stones in sight? Dissolve, don't just slice!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ursodeoxycholic Acid. The presence of gallstones with a \"normal wall\" on ultrasound indicates uncomplicated cholelithiasis, making medical dissolution a viable initial management strategy, especially for cholesterol stones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUrsodeoxycholic Acid (UDCA) is a naturally occurring bile acid that works by reducing the cholesterol saturation of bile, thereby facilitating the dissolution of cholesterol gallstones. It is most effective for small, non-calcified cholesterol stones in a functioning gallbladder. This approach avoids surgery and is suitable for patients who are not surgical candidates or prefer a non-invasive option when the gallbladder wall shows no signs of acute inflammation or thickening.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (Lap chole) (Incorrect): While laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the definitive treatment for symptomatic cholelithiasis, the key phrase \"normal wall\" suggests the absence of acute cholecystitis or other complications that would necessitate immediate surgical intervention. For uncomplicated, symptomatic gallstones with a normal gallbladder wall, medical dissolution with UDCA can be considered as a first-line treatment, particularly if the stones are cholesterol-rich and small.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ursodeoxycholic Acid (UDCA) | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Indication | Symptomatic cholesterol gallstones, normal GB wall, small stones, patient unfit for surgery or prefers non-invasive | Symptomatic gallstones (biliary colic, cholecystitis, pancreatitis), complications (choledocholithiasis, perforation) |\n| Mechanism | Reduces cholesterol saturation in bile, dissolves cholesterol stones | Surgical removal of the gallbladder |\n| Efficacy | Variable, best for small, non-calcified stones; high recurrence rate | Definitive cure, low recurrence |\n| Risks | Diarrhea, nausea, rare liver issues | Surgical risks (bleeding, infection, bile duct injury, bile leak) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal GB wall + stones = consider medical dissolution first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would see echogenic foci (stones) within the gallbladder lumen, often with posterior acoustic shadowing. Crucially, the gallbladder wall thickness would be normal (typically <3 mm), with no pericholecystic fluid or sonographic Murphy's sign, indicating the absence of acute inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) 2010 guidelines on the management of gallstone disease recommend UDCA for selected patients with symptomatic cholesterol gallstones who are not candidates for surgery or prefer medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Lap chole | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Ursodeoxycholic | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: b) Ursodeoxycholic Acid, is a naturally occurring bile acid and is used to dissolve gallstones that are** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
