  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the CBD goes high, Roux-en-Y is the way!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHepaticojejunostomy is the correct management for a transected common bile duct (CBD) above the level of the cystic duct. This injury represents a significant disruption of the main biliary drainage system, necessitating a reconstructive procedure to restore bile flow from the liver to the gastrointestinal tract.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy is the gold standard for high-level bile duct injuries, particularly those involving the common hepatic duct or its bifurcation. This procedure involves anastomosing the proximal transected bile duct (or common hepatic duct) to a Roux limb of the jejunum, typically 40-60 cm long. The Roux-en-Y configuration prevents reflux of intestinal contents into the biliary tree, which is critical for preventing ascending cholangitis and subsequent stricture formation, thereby ensuring long-term patency and reducing morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (hepaticoduodenostomy) (Incorrect): While it connects the bile duct to the duodenum, it is generally avoided for high bile duct injuries due to the significant risk of reflux cholangitis, which can lead to recurrent infections and strictures. The direct connection allows duodenal contents to easily enter the biliary system.\nOption C (choledocho- duodenostomy) (Incorrect): Similar to hepaticoduodenostomy, this procedure connects the common bile duct to the duodenum. It carries a higher risk of reflux cholangitis and 'sump syndrome' compared to a Roux-en-Y reconstruction, especially for high injuries. It is typically reserved for specific benign conditions or lower CBD obstructions, not high transections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hepaticojejunostomy (Roux-en-Y) | High CBD/CHD injury, benign strictures, choledochal cysts | Gold standard for high injuries, prevents reflux cholangitis | More complex, longer operative time |\n| Choledochoduodenostomy | Lower CBD obstruction (e.g., stone, distal stricture), pancreatic head resection | Simpler, shorter operative time | Risk of reflux cholangitis, sump syndrome |\n| Primary Repair/T-tube | Small, clean transection of CBD (often lower), iatrogenic injury | Simplest, preserves anatomy | Risk of stricture, T-tube complications |\n| Choledochojejunostomy (Roux-en-Y) | Lower CBD injury requiring bypass, choledochal cysts | Prevents reflux cholangitis | More complex, longer operative time |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High bile duct injury? Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy is the definitive repair.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the completely transected common bile duct (or common hepatic duct) above the cystic duct, often with surrounding inflammation or tissue loss. Intraoperative cholangiography would confirm the level of injury and delineate the proximal biliary tree, ensuring no other injuries or retained stones are present before reconstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Spotlight Review: Management of Bile Duct Injuries (2018) recommends Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy as the preferred method for definitive repair of major bile duct injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hepaticoduodenostomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hepaticojejunostomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | choledocho- duodenostomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
