  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait for disaster; remove symptomatic stones!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This patient presented with classic symptoms of symptomatic cholelithiasis, likely biliary colic with transient obstruction, which warrants definitive surgical management despite the temporary improvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSymptomatic cholelithiasis, characterized by RUQ pain, jaundice, and fever, indicates gallstones causing obstruction or inflammation. Even if the acute episode resolves spontaneously, the underlying pathology of gallstones remains, posing a significant risk for recurrent symptoms and severe complications such as acute cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, gallstone pancreatitis, or recurrent cholangitis. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy offers a minimally invasive and definitive solution by removing the diseased gallbladder, thereby eliminating the source of these potential future morbidities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Follow up\" is inappropriate for symptomatic gallstones. The patient has already experienced symptoms (pain, jaundice, fever), indicating the stones are not benign and will likely cause further, potentially more severe, episodes.\nOption C (Incorrect): Ursodeoxycholic acid is primarily used for dissolving small, non-calcified cholesterol stones in asymptomatic patients or those unfit for surgery. It is ineffective for pigmented stones, large stones, or in patients with a history of symptomatic episodes like this one.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Symptoms | US Findings | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Asymptomatic Cholelithiasis | None | Gallstones, normal GB | Observation (unless specific risk factors) |\n| Biliary Colic | RUQ pain, often post-prandial, resolves | Gallstones, normal GB | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | Persistent RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis | Gallstones, GB wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, Murphy's sign | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (urgent/early) |\n| Choledocholithiasis | RUQ pain, jaundice, fever (Charcot's triad) | CBD dilation, stones in CBD | ERCP +/- Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic gallstones, even if symptoms resolve, require cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound showing multiple gallstones within a normal-walled gallbladder confirms cholelithiasis without acute cholecystitis. The \"normal-walled\" aspect is key to differentiating from acute cholecystitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) guidelines for the clinical application of laparoscopic cholecystectomy (2010, updated periodically) recommend laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | lap choly | ✅ Correct |\n| B | follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ursodeoxycholic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
