  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fever post-bariatric? Think deep, image fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, CT abdomen. Persistent fever for a week after bariatric surgery, especially with a normal external examination, strongly suggests an intra-abdominal complication like an abscess or anastomotic leak, which necessitates advanced imaging for diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatients undergoing bariatric surgery are at significant risk for specific intra-abdominal complications, including anastomotic leaks, intra-abdominal abscesses, and internal hernias. These serious issues can present with non-specific symptoms such as persistent fever, tachycardia, and abdominal pain, even when the external wound appears benign. A fever lasting a week, despite a normal physical exam, mandates a thorough investigation for deep-seated pathology. CT abdomen with oral and intravenous contrast is the gold standard for accurately identifying these critical intra-abdominal complications, allowing for timely intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Reassure) (Incorrect): Persistent fever for a week post-surgery is never normal and indicates an underlying pathological process that requires investigation, not reassurance.\nOption C (Chest x-ray) (Incorrect): While pulmonary complications can cause fever, the question states \"chest... normal,\" making a primary pulmonary source less likely. Given the context of bariatric surgery, intra-abdominal complications are a higher priority for investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom/Sign | Potential Cause (Post-Bariatric) | Initial Workup |\n| :----------- | :------------------------------- | :--------------- |\n| Persistent fever, normal exam | Anastomotic leak, intra-abdominal abscess | CT abdomen with contrast |\n| Early fever, cough, dyspnea | Atelectasis, pneumonia | Chest X-ray, O2 sats |\n| Wound erythema, pain, discharge | Wound infection | Local exam, wound culture |\n| Leg pain, swelling | Deep vein thrombosis (DVT) | Duplex ultrasound |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Persistent post-op fever demands imaging for deep collections, especially after bariatric surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT abdomen, one might observe fluid collections, abscesses (often with gas bubbles), extravasation of oral contrast (indicating a leak), or signs of inflammation around anastomotic sites.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines for the Clinical Application of Bariatric Surgery (2016/2022). These guidelines recommend prompt investigation, including imaging, for suspected leaks or abscesses in patients with persistent fever or abdominal pain post-bariatric surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Reassure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT abdomen | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Chest x-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Keyword: : Spiking fever > deep collections** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
