  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When cholangitis strikes, ERCP is the key to drain and thrive.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nERCP is the correct next investigation for acute cholangitis. This condition is a medical emergency caused by biliary obstruction and infection, requiring prompt decompression. ERCP offers both diagnostic visualization and immediate therapeutic intervention to relieve the obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholangitis necessitates urgent biliary decompression to prevent sepsis and organ failure. ERCP is the gold standard because it allows for direct visualization of the biliary tree, sphincterotomy, stone extraction, and/or stent placement to restore bile flow. This immediate therapeutic capability is critical for managing the infection and improving patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (US) (Incorrect): Ultrasound is typically the initial imaging modality for suspected biliary pathology, useful for detecting gallstones and ductal dilation. However, it is often insufficient for definitive diagnosis of the cause of obstruction or for therapeutic intervention in acute cholangitis.\nOption B (MRCP) (Incorrect): MRCP is an excellent non-invasive diagnostic tool for detailed visualization of the biliary tree and identifying stones or strictures. While highly diagnostic, it is purely imaging-based and does not offer the therapeutic capabilities essential for managing acute cholangitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Role in Cholangitis | Diagnostic/Therapeutic | Key Advantage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **US** | Initial screening for obstruction/stones | Diagnostic | Non-invasive, readily available, no radiation |\n| **MRCP** | Detailed anatomical mapping, identify cause of obstruction | Diagnostic | Non-invasive, no radiation, good for complex anatomy |\n| **ERCP** | Definitive diagnosis and immediate decompression | Diagnostic & Therapeutic | Gold standard for intervention, immediate relief of obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute cholangitis = ERCP for diagnosis and decompression.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ERCP, one would typically see dilated bile ducts, often with impacted stones in the distal common bile duct, or strictures. Pus may be seen draining from the papilla, confirming the diagnosis of cholangitis. The question mentions a 'Typical pic of acute cholangitis,' which would likely show dilated ducts and potentially stones on initial imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 (TG18) for the diagnosis and management of acute cholangitis and cholecystitis. TG18 recommends urgent biliary drainage (often via ERCP) for severe acute cholangitis and for moderate cases unresponsive to initial medical management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ERCP | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Cholangitis is an inflammation of the bile duct system it happened bez** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
