  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ERCP a dilated CBD without a compelling reason!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is cholecystectomy. This patient presents with classic symptoms of symptomatic cholelithiasis (biliary colic after a fatty meal) and ultrasound findings consistent with chronic cholecystitis (multiple stones, thick wall).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSymptomatic cholelithiasis is a primary indication for cholecystectomy. While a dilated common bile duct (CBD) of 12mm is concerning for choledocholithiasis, in the absence of jaundice, cholangitis, or pancreatitis, it does not automatically necessitate pre-operative ERCP. The immediate next step is to address the symptomatic gallbladder. Intraoperative cholangiogram (IOC) or magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) can be considered to further evaluate the CBD if suspicion for choledocholithiasis remains high after cholecystectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (ERCP) is incorrect: ERCP is an invasive procedure with potential complications. It is indicated for confirmed or highly suspected choledocholithiasis, especially in the presence of cholangitis, pancreatitis, or persistent jaundice. A dilated CBD alone, without other signs of obstruction or infection, does not mandate pre-operative ERCP over cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cholecystectomy Indication | ERCP Indication |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Symptoms** | Biliary colic, chronic abdominal pain after fatty meals | Cholangitis, pancreatitis, persistent jaundice, severe biliary obstruction |\n| **US Findings** | Gallbladder stones, thick wall, sludge, polyps | Dilated CBD with stones, dilated intrahepatic ducts |\n| **Labs** | Normal LFTs (typically), normal amylase/lipase | Elevated LFTs (especially direct bilirubin), elevated amylase/lipase, leukocytosis |\n| **Timing** | Elective for symptomatic cholelithiasis, urgent for acute cholecystitis | Urgent/emergent for acute cholangitis/pancreatitis, elective for confirmed CBD stones without complications |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic cholelithiasis + dilated CBD without cholangitis = Cholecystectomy first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, multiple gallbladder stones and a thick gallbladder wall are classic findings for chronic cholecystitis. A CBD diameter of 12mm is significantly dilated, suggesting prior or current obstruction, but without other signs of acute obstruction or infection, it doesn't preclude proceeding with cholecystectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Guidelines for the Clinical Application of Laparoscopic Biliary Surgery (2020) recommend cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis. They also suggest that a dilated CBD alone, without other signs of choledocholithiasis, does not mandate pre-operative ERCP.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ERCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
