  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ERCP's duodenal dance can lead to a dangerous tear.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duodenal. After a long ERCP, a patient presenting with hypotension and pain strongly suggests a perforation, and the duodenum is the most common site of injury due to the nature of the procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nERCP involves passing an endoscope through the esophagus and stomach into the duodenum to access the ampulla of Vater. The second part of the duodenum, where the papilla is located, is particularly susceptible to injury during cannulation, wire manipulation, and especially sphincterotomy. The retroperitoneal location of the second and third parts of the duodenum means perforations here can lead to retroperitoneal air and fluid, which can be insidious but rapidly lead to sepsis and hemodynamic instability if not recognized and managed promptly.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Esophagus - Incorrect): While the endoscope passes through the esophagus, perforations here are exceedingly rare during ERCP itself, typically associated with diagnostic EGD or therapeutic esophageal procedures.\nOption C (Gastric - Incorrect): The stomach is traversed but is a much less common site of perforation during ERCP compared to the duodenum, as the primary manipulation and instrumentation occur distally.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Typical Presentation | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Post-ERCP Pancreatitis | 3-5% | Epigastric pain, elevated amylase/lipase | Supportive, NPO, IV fluids |\n| Perforation | 0.1-1% | Abdominal pain, fever, hypotension, free air | Conservative vs. surgical repair |\n| Bleeding | 0.5-2% | Hematemesis, melena, drop in Hgb | Endoscopic hemostasis vs. surgery |\n| Cholangitis | <1% | Fever, RUQ pain, jaundice | Antibiotics, drainage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duodenal perforation is the most common and feared complication of ERCP.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, free retroperitoneal air or fluid collections adjacent to the duodenum, particularly in the second or third part, are highly suggestive of perforation. Intraoperatively, a visible tear in the duodenal wall, often near the ampulla, would be identified.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASGE (American Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy) Guidelines for the management of ERCP complications (e.g., 2010, 2019 updates) recommend prompt recognition and tailored management of perforations, often favoring conservative management for small retroperitoneal perforations and surgical intervention for larger or intraluminal perforations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Esophagus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duodenal | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Gastric | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
