  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder is angry, take it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This patient presents with classic signs of acute cholecystitis (RUQ pain, thickened gallbladder wall, pericystic fluid, stones), and definitive surgical removal of the inflamed gallbladder is the gold standard treatment for stable patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis is primarily caused by cystic duct obstruction by a gallstone, leading to inflammation and distension. The presence of pericystic fluid indicates significant inflammation. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy offers definitive treatment by removing the source of inflammation and preventing recurrence, while also allowing for direct visualization and management of any local complications. Early cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) is associated with better outcomes and reduced complications compared to delayed surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Percutaneous drainage is a temporizing measure for acute cholecystitis, typically reserved for critically ill patients or those with severe comorbidities who are not surgical candidates. It does not remove the underlying cause (stones) and carries a risk of recurrence, making it not the *best* definitive intervention for a generally stable patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | Percutaneous Cholecystostomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Definitive treatment for acute cholecystitis in stable patients | Temporizing measure for critically ill/high-risk patients, or severe local inflammation |\n| **Goal** | Remove inflamed gallbladder, prevent recurrence | Decompress gallbladder, reduce inflammation, stabilize patient |\n| **Efficacy** | High, definitive cure | Symptomatic relief, not curative for cholelithiasis |\n| **Risks** | Surgical risks (bleeding, bile duct injury, infection) | Catheter-related complications (dislodgement, infection, bile leak) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute cholecystitis with stones = definitive surgery if patient is stable.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound findings of gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericystic fluid, and gallstones are highly suggestive of acute cholecystitis. Intraoperatively, one would expect to see an inflamed, edematous, and possibly distended gallbladder with surrounding inflammatory exudate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 recommend early laparoscopic cholecystectomy for Grade I and II acute cholecystitis, and for Grade III after initial resuscitation and stabilization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | percutaneous drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Laparoscopic cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
