  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small polyp, big responsibility: always follow up.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"follow up.\" A 0.6cm biliary polyp, while small, still warrants surveillance due to its potential for growth or malignant transformation, making simple reassurance inappropriate.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary polyps are often discovered incidentally and their management is primarily guided by size and risk factors. Polyps less than 1 cm, like this 0.6cm lesion, are typically managed with active surveillance, usually via serial ultrasound, to monitor for growth or changes. This approach balances the low immediate malignant risk with the need to detect any progression early.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"reassure.\" This is incorrect because even small biliary polyps carry a risk of malignancy or can grow over time, necessitating a structured follow-up plan rather than complete reassurance without monitoring.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Size | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| < 6 mm | Annual ultrasound surveillance | Very low malignant potential, but monitor for growth |\n| 6-9 mm | 6-month then annual ultrasound surveillance | Intermediate risk, closer monitoring initially |\n| ≥ 10 mm | Cholecystectomy | Higher malignant potential, especially if sessile or rapidly growing |\n| Any size with symptoms, rapid growth, or primary sclerosing cholangitis | Cholecystectomy | Concerning features or high-risk patient population warrant resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biliary polyps: size dictates surveillance frequency or need for surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a biliary polyp typically appears as a non-shadowing, non-mobile echogenic lesion protruding into the gallbladder lumen. It is distinct from gallstones, which are mobile and cast acoustic shadows.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Gastroenterological Association (AGA) guidelines (2020) recommend surveillance for gallbladder polyps <10mm, with specific intervals based on size and patient risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | reassure. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | follow up | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
