  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When air meets diaphragm, think ulcer's wrath!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe presence of sudden epigastric pain radiating to the back, coupled with free air under the diaphragm on X-ray, is pathognomonic for a perforated viscus. A perforated duodenal ulcer is the most common cause of this classic presentation, necessitating immediate surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA perforated duodenal ulcer results in the leakage of gastric or duodenal contents, including air, into the peritoneal cavity. This free air accumulates under the diaphragm, which is readily visible on an upright chest X-ray as a crescent-shaped lucency. The sudden onset of severe epigastric pain, often radiating to the back or shoulder, is due to chemical peritonitis caused by the spilled contents, a critical surgical emergency.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (acute pancreatic) (Incorrect): While acute pancreatitis can cause severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, it does not typically cause free air under the diaphragm. Its diagnosis relies on elevated pancreatic enzymes and characteristic imaging findings like pancreatic edema or necrosis, not pneumoperitoneum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Perforated Duodenal Ulcer | Acute Pancreatitis |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Pain** | Sudden, severe epigastric, radiates to back/shoulder | Gradual/sudden, severe epigastric, radiates to back |\n| **Imaging (X-ray)** | Free air under diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum) | No free air; sentinel loop/colon cutoff sign possible |\n| **Imaging (CT)** | Free air, fluid, ulcer crater | Pancreatic edema, inflammation, necrosis, fluid collections |\n| **Diagnosis** | Clinical, X-ray, CT | Clinical, elevated amylase/lipase, CT |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Air under diaphragm = perforated viscus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upright chest X-ray, free air under the diaphragm appears as a distinct, crescent-shaped radiolucency separating the liver (right) or spleen (left) from the diaphragm. Intraoperatively, one would observe a visible perforation, typically on the anterior surface of the duodenum, with spillage of gastric/duodenal contents and air.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020). These guidelines recommend prompt diagnosis and surgical intervention (e.g., Graham patch repair) for perforated peptic ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | perforated duodenal ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | acute pancreatic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
