  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Twisted gut, massive balloon, act fast or face doom.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSigmoid volvulus is the correct answer. The clinical presentation of an elderly male with constipation and abdominal pain, coupled with an X-ray showing a massively enlarged loop, is highly characteristic of sigmoid volvulus, which is a closed-loop obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid volvulus occurs when the sigmoid colon, often redundant and with a long mesentery, twists on its mesenteric axis. This twisting creates a closed-loop obstruction, leading to massive dilation of the affected segment due to trapped gas and fluid. The compromised blood supply from the mesenteric twist can rapidly lead to ischemia, necrosis, and perforation, making early recognition and intervention critical. The classic X-ray finding of a massively dilated, inverted U-shaped loop (coffee bean sign) extending into the upper abdomen is pathognomonic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute diverticulitis) (Incorrect): While acute diverticulitis can cause abdominal pain and constipation, it typically presents with localized left lower quadrant pain, fever, and leukocytosis. X-rays usually show signs of ileus or free air if perforated, but not the massively enlarged, dilated loop characteristic of a closed-loop obstruction like volvulus. Ascites is also not a typical feature of uncomplicated diverticulitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sigmoid Volvulus | Acute Diverticulitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Typical Patient** | Elderly, chronically constipated, institutionalized | Middle-aged to elderly, often with history of diverticulosis |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Abdominal pain, constipation, distension, nausea/vomiting | Left lower quadrant pain, fever, leukocytosis, change in bowel habits |\n| **X-ray Findings** | Massively dilated, inverted U-shaped loop (coffee bean sign), loss of haustral markings | Localized ileus, free air (if perforated), soft tissue mass |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Twisting of sigmoid colon on its mesentery, causing closed-loop obstruction | Inflammation/infection of diverticula, often due to fecalith obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Elderly + constipation + massively dilated loop on X-ray = Sigmoid Volvulus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, sigmoid volvulus classically appears as a massively dilated, gas-filled loop of bowel, often described as an 'inverted U' or 'coffee bean sign,' extending from the pelvis into the upper abdomen, sometimes reaching the right upper quadrant. Haustral markings are typically absent. CT scan would show the 'whirl sign' (mesenteric vessels twisting) and a dilated sigmoid colon.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016) recommends initial endoscopic detorsion for stable patients with sigmoid volvulus, followed by elective resection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sigmoid volvulus | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute diverticulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
