  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PSC means IBD until proven otherwise; scope 'em!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Colonoscopy. Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) has a very strong association with Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD), particularly ulcerative colitis. Therefore, screening for IBD with a colonoscopy is a critical initial step in the management of a patient diagnosed with PSC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary Sclerosing Cholangitis is a chronic cholestatic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts, leading to strictures. A significant majority, approximately 70-80%, of patients with PSC also have co-existing IBD, with ulcerative colitis being the most common form. This association is so strong that a diagnosis of PSC mandates a thorough evaluation for IBD, even if the patient is asymptomatic, as the IBD can be quiescent or present atypically. Colonoscopy is the gold standard for diagnosing and assessing the extent of IBD.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT - Incorrect): While CT can visualize bile duct abnormalities and rule out other causes of cholestasis, it is not the primary diagnostic modality for PSC (MRCP is preferred) nor for screening for associated IBD. It does not provide the mucosal detail necessary to diagnose inflammatory bowel disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Diagnostic Test | Associated Condition | Management Implication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) | MRCP | Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD), especially Ulcerative Colitis | Colonoscopy for IBD screening/surveillance |\n| Primary Biliary Cholangitis (PBC) | Antimitochondrial Antibodies (AMA) | Other autoimmune diseases (e.g., Sjogren's, Scleroderma) | Ursodeoxycholic acid, symptomatic treatment |\n| Cholangiocarcinoma | MRCP, Biopsy | PSC, Liver flukes, choledochal cysts | Surgical resection, palliation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSC and IBD are inseparable; always colonoscopy for PSC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRCP, PSC typically presents with multifocal stricturing and dilations of the intrahepatic and/or extrahepatic bile ducts, giving a characteristic 'beaded' appearance. Colonoscopy in a patient with associated IBD would reveal mucosal inflammation, friability, ulcerations, or pseudopolyps consistent with ulcerative colitis or Crohn's disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance on Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (2023) strongly recommends that all patients with PSC undergo a colonoscopy at diagnosis to screen for inflammatory bowel disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Colonoscopy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
