  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 High speed demands scans, even when stable.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT. Despite the patient being stable and wearing a seatbelt, a high-velocity motor vehicle accident (MVA) carries a significant risk of occult injuries that require comprehensive imaging for detection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHigh-speed trauma (130 km/h) indicates a substantial transfer of kinetic energy, which can cause severe internal injuries even in the absence of immediate hemodynamic instability or altered consciousness. A seatbelt, while protective, can also cause specific injury patterns (e.g., 'seatbelt sign' leading to hollow viscus injury, mesenteric tears, or lumbar spine fractures). In a stable trauma patient, a CT scan is the gold standard for evaluating the head, neck, chest, abdomen, and pelvis, providing detailed anatomical information to identify solid organ lacerations, hollow viscus injuries, vascular damage, and skeletal fractures, thereby guiding appropriate management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (us of abdomen) (Incorrect): While a FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is rapid and useful for detecting free fluid in unstable patients, it is operator-dependent, has limited sensitivity for retroperitoneal injuries, bowel injuries, and solid organ parenchymal damage, and does not provide the comprehensive detail needed for a stable patient after high-velocity trauma.\nOption C (laparotomy) (Incorrect): Laparotomy is a therapeutic intervention, not a diagnostic one for a stable patient. It is reserved for unstable patients with clear signs of intra-abdominal hemorrhage or peritonitis, or after imaging has confirmed a surgical pathology requiring intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Indication (Stable/Unstable) | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Scan | Stable trauma, high suspicion of injury | Comprehensive, detailed, identifies occult injuries | Radiation exposure, contrast risk, requires stable patient |\n| FAST Exam (US) | Unstable trauma, rapid assessment for free fluid | Rapid, portable, no radiation | Operator dependent, limited view of retroperitoneum/bowel, not definitive for all injuries |\n| Laparotomy | Unstable with clear signs of hemorrhage/peritonitis, or confirmed surgical injury | Definitive treatment, direct visualization | Invasive, risks of surgery, not a primary diagnostic tool for stable patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High-velocity trauma + stable patient = comprehensive CT scan.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, one would look for solid organ lacerations (e.g., splenic, hepatic, renal), retroperitoneal hematomas, free fluid (blood), bowel wall thickening, pneumoperitoneum, mesenteric hematomas, and spinal fractures, all indicative of significant energy transfer.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) 11th Edition (2022) recommends that for stable trauma patients with suspected torso injury, a CT scan is the preferred diagnostic modality after the primary and secondary surveys to identify injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT | ✅ Correct |\n| B | us of abdomen. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 515158176-Surgery-2020-with-correction-docx-docx-docx.docx**\n",
